{"title_page": "Earthling (album)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Earthling\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover      = Earthling (album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|1997|2|3}}\n| recorded   = March \u2013 August 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{ubl|[[Mountain Studios|Mountain]] ([[Montreux]], Switzerland)|Looking Glass (Manhattan, NY)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glassnyc.com/contact.htm|title=THE LOOKING GLASS STUDIOS}}</ref>}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Industrial rock]]<ref name=DT96>{{citation|url=http://www.davidbowie.se/bassman/articles/96/tm.html |title=A Star Comes Back to Earth After a Lifetime of Identity Crisis |date=14 December 1996 |first=Mick |last=Brown |accessdate=2 August 2013 |journal=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>|[[electronica]]<ref name=\"EWFeb97\"/>|[[drum and bass]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stereogum.com/1291641/david-bowie-albums-from-worst-to-best/franchises/counting-down/attachment/earthling/ | title=David Bowie Albums From Worst To Best: Earthling | work=[[Stereogum]] | date=22 March 2013 | accessdate=25 June 2015 | author=Lariviere, Aaron}}</ref>|[[oldschool jungle|jungle]]<ref name=\"allmusic review\"/>|[[techno]]<ref name=\"allmusic review\"/>}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=48|s=57}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Arista Records|Arista]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[Reeves Gabrels]]|[[Mark Plati]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[Hours (David Bowie album)|Hours]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Earthling\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Telling Lies]]\n | single1date = 4 November 1996\n | single2     = [[Little Wonder (song)|Little Wonder]]\n | single2date = 27 January 1997\n | single3     = [[Dead Man Walking (song)|Dead Man Walking]]\n | single3date = 14 April 1997\n | single4     = Seven Years in Tibet\n | single4date = 18 August 1997 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Singles/SYIT1997/Title.html|title=Seven Years In Tibet|website=www.teenagewildlife.com|accessdate=26 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116174543/http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Singles/SYIT1997/Title.html|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n | single5     = [[I'm Afraid of Americans]]\n | single5date = 14 October 1997\n}}\n}}\n'''''Earthling''''' (stylised as '''''EART HL I NG''''') is the 20th studio album by English recording artist [[David Bowie]]. It was originally released in February 1997 on [[Arista Records]]. The album showcases an [[electronica]]-influenced sound partly inspired by the [[Industrial music|industrial]] and [[drum and bass]] culture of the 1990s.<ref name=GuitarPlayer97>{{citation | title=Changes 2.1 | first=Joe | last=Gore | journal=[[Guitar Player]] | date=June 1997| pages=45\u201358}}</ref>\n\n==Background and development==\nBowie returned to the studio five days after finishing the [[Outside Tour|tour]] for his previous album, ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|1. Outside]]'' (1995). About a week after the album's release, Bowie told an interviewer, \"I really thought it would be great if we could do a photo, almost a sonic photograph of what we were like at that time. So, [[Reeves Gabrels|Reeves [Gabrels]]] and I started writing immediately after we finished on the road.\"<ref name=Bowie50>{{Citation| last=Laban| first=Linda| title=Bowie Hits a Fab 50 | journal=[[The Seattle Times]] | date=13 February 1997 | pages=E3}}</ref> Despite going into the studio with no material ready,<ref name=RayGun97 /> the album took only {{frac|2|1|2}} weeks to record<ref name=Bowie50 /> (typical for a Bowie album).<ref name=MMReview>{{Citation | last=Isler| first=Scott| title=David Bowie Opens Up \u2013 A Little | journal=Musician| issue=106|date=August 1987 | pages=60\u201373}}</ref> Bowie compared it to 1980's ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]'': \"I think there's quite a link between ''Scary Monsters'' and this album, to a certain extent. Certainly, the same intensity of aggression.\"<ref name=Fi>\"David Bowie: The FI Interview\" by J.D. Considine, Fi magazine, October 1997, pp 36\u201341</ref> Bowie described the album as an effort \"to produce some really dynamic, aggressive-sounding material.\"<ref name=Bowie50 />\n\n\"Unlike most [[drum and bass]] things,\" he noted, \"we didn't just take parts from other people's records and sample them. On the snare drum stuff, [[Zack Alford|Zac [Alford]]] went away and did his own loops and worked out all kinds of strange timings and rhythms. Then we speeded those up to your regular 160 beats per minute. That's very much how we treat the album. We kept all sampling in-house and created our own soundscape in a way.\"<ref name=Bowie50 />\n\n''Earthling'' was the first Bowie album recorded entirely digitally, \"entirely on [[Hard disk drive|hard disk]].\"<ref name=GuitarPlayer97 /> During interviews promoting the album, Bowie said, \"I did nearly everything on the guitar. A lot of screechy-scrawly stuff was done on saxophone, then transferred to sampler, and then distorted and worked on the synthesizer.\"<ref name=Fi />\n\nBowie and Gabrels used a technique they'd started while working on ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|1. Outside]]'': transferring bits of guitar to a sampling keyboard and constructing riffs from those pieces. \"It's real guitar,\" said Bowie, \"but constructed in a synthetic way. But [[Brian Eno]] got in the way \u2013 in the nicest possible way \u2013 so we didn't get to that until this album. We want to go further with that, because it's a very exciting idea.\"<ref name=GuitarPlayer97 /> Bowie considered this album, along with its predecessor, to be a \"textural diary\" of what the last few years of the millennium felt like.<ref name=AX95>{{Citation | last=Paul | first=George A. | title=Bowie Outside Looking In | journal=Axcess Magazine | volume=3 | issue=5 | year=1995 | pages=60\u201362}}</ref>\n\nBowie's and Gabrels' influences had a big impact on the album: Bowie was influenced by a \"euro\" sound and bands like [[the Prodigy]], while Gabrels was into American [[Industrial music]] and bands like [[Underworld (band)|Underworld]].<ref name=GuitarPlayer97 />\n\n:{{quote|\"There was talk that the album was jumping on the drum 'n' bass bandwagon, but it's more influenced by what came to be called [[electronica]]. David loved [[Photek]] and [[Tricky (musician)|Tricky]]. Those influences were in the air at the time. I never told David this, but in my head I was thinking more of '[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]' \u2013 the muscular rock band with sequential information\u2026 It's my favourite record that I did with David. We did have a sense while we were doing it that we were making something we hadn't heard.\" \u2013 [[Reeves Gabrels]]<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Bill|last=DeMain|title=Reeves Gabrels talks about David Bowie|magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|issue=247|date=April 2018|page=58}}</ref>}}\n\n\"(For ''[[Young Americans]]'') I wanted to work within the [[Philadelphia soul]] experience, and the only way that I knew was to bring what's thoroughly European about me to this intrinsically black American format,\" Bowie noted. \"And this [album was] not a dissimilar situation. It was the hybridizing of the European and the American sensibilities, and for me, that's exciting. That's what I do best. I'm a synthesist.<ref name=Live97>{{Citation | last=Pond | first=Steve | title=Beyond Bowie | journal=Live! Magazine | volume=2 |issue=2 |date=March 1997}}</ref>\n\n\"I guess the common ground with all the songs is this abiding need in me to vacillate between [[atheism]] or a kind of [[gnosticism]],\" he said. \"I keep going backwards and forwards between the two things, because they mean a lot in my life. I mean, the church doesn't enter into my writing, or my thought; I have no empathy with any organised religions. What I need is to find a balance, spiritually, with the way I live and my demise. And that period of time \u2013 from today until my demise \u2013 is the only thing that fascinates me.<ref name=Q97X>{{Citation | last=Cavanagh | first=David | title=ChangesFiftyBowie | journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q magazine]] |date=February 1997 | pages=52\u201359}}</ref>\n\nThe album cover showcases a [[Union Jack]]-based coat by [[Alexander McQueen]], who had designed stage costumes for Bowie and his band.<ref name=CNN13>{{citation | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/03/22/showbiz/uk-david-bowie-exhibition | title=Bowie exhibition charts life of pop's ultimate Starman | accessdate=10 April 2013 | last=Wilkinson | first=Peter | work=CNN | date=22 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nBefore the album was released, Bowie considered using ''Earthlings'' (plural) for its title.<ref name=YTE96>{{YouTube|id=dBKLcINEs-c|title=David Bowie- Little Wonder (Pre-Earthling Live Version at D.C. 1996)}}</ref>\n\n==Song development==\nBowie and the band continued their experimental approach to making music, first used in the [[Berlin Trilogy]]: for the track \"Looking for Satellites\", Bowie told guitarist Gabrels that he \"only wanted him to play on one string at a time. ... He was hemmed in by the chord until it changed, and that made his run-up most unorthodox.\" The guitar riff used for the track \"Dead Man Walking\" was based on a pattern [[Jimmy Page]] (of [[Led Zeppelin]]) had played for Bowie back in the '60s. According to Gabrels, part of the bass track on \"Little Wonder\" was a recording of bassist [[Gail Ann Dorsey]] as she tried to get a sound from her pedalboard while not knowing she was being recorded. For \"Battle for Britain\", Bowie challenged [[Mike Garson]] to play based on \"the idea from a piece of [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]] wrote called \"Ragtime for Eleven Instruments\". I said 'If you could kind of get into the character of that...' and he did it immediately.\"<ref name=Fi />\n\n\"[[Little Wonder (song)|Little Wonder]]\" was one of the first tracks Bowie and Gabrels wrote for the album,<ref name=Fi /> and Bowie called writing the track a \"ridiculous\" exercise in pure stream of consciousness. \"I just picked [[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarves]] and made a line for each of the dwarves' names. And that's the song [laughs]. And then I ran out of dwarves' names, so there's new dwarves in it like 'Stinky'.\"<ref name=RayGun97>{{Citation | last=Kuipers | first=Dean | title=David Bowie: Is There Life on Earth? | journal=Raygun Magazine | issue=44 |date=March 1997}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, Bowie thought he'd only have a few new songs for the album, and had intended to fill out the album with remakes of some of his past songs, including \"Dead Against It\" (from his 1993 \"soundtrack\" ''[[The Buddha of Suburbia (album)|The Buddha of Suburbia]]''), \"[[I Can't Read]]\" and \"[[Baby Universal]]\" from his time with [[Tin Machine]], and \"[[Bring Me the Disco King]]\", which he'd tried his hand at once before in 1993 for his ''[[Black Tie White Noise]]'' album.<ref name=\"A2A\">{{cite book | title=Ashes to Ashes The Songs of David Bowie 1976\u20132016 | first=Chris | last=O'Leary | publisher=[[Repeater Books]]  | year=2019 | isbn=9781912248308}}</ref> But, due to his unexpectedly prolific songwriting during the sessions, none of these songs were released on the album, although Bowie did in fact record new versions of \"Bring Me the Disco King\" and \"Baby Universal\".<ref name=\"A2A\" /> Of the latter, Bowie said \"I thought [it] was a really good song and I don't think it got heard. I didn't really want that to happen to it, so I put in on this album. I really like this. I think this version is very good.\"<ref name=\"MVS96\">{{citation|last=Haefeli|first=Mark|title=Music Video Shoot|url=http://www.davidbowie.se/bassman/articles/96/mvs.html|year=1996|accessdate=24 May 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> The re-recorded version of \"[[I Can't Read]]\" was released on [[The Ice Storm (soundtrack)|the soundtrack]] for the movie ''[[The Ice Storm (film)|The Ice Storm]]'', and the re-recorded \"Baby Universal\" would be released in 2020 as part of the intermittently-released EP ''Is it Any Wonder?''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowie |first1=David |title=Baby Universal '97 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d8FG0IH3ths |website=YouTub |publisher=Parlophone/ISO |accessdate=31 January 2020 |ref=Parlophone/ISO |format=Video |date=Jan 30, 2020}}</ref> Bowie also re-recorded \"[[I'm Afraid of Americans]]\", having recorded a version for the [[Showgirls (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for the 1995 movie ''[[Showgirls]]'' during his ''Outside'' studio sessions: Bowie said \"That was something that Eno and I put together, and I just didn't feel it fit ''Outside'', so it didn't go on it. It just got left behind. So then we took just the embryo of it, and restructured it with this band.\"<ref name=Fi /> Additionally, Bowie included \"[[Telling Lies]]\", which Bowie had written and released on the Internet the year before.<ref name=\"A2A\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[AllMusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic review\">{{cite web |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |title=Review: ''Earthling \u2013 David Bowie'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r246896|pure_url=yes}} |website=Allmusic |accessdate=3 August 2009 |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|4}}<ref name=chicagotribune>{{citation |title=David Bowie Earthling (Virgin) |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-14/entertainment/9702140375_1_david-bowie-reeves-gabrels-earthling |journal=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=28 August 2013 |date=14 February 1997 | first=Greg | last=Kot}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |edition=5th concise |year=2011 |last=Larkin |first=Colin |authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer) |title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score =  A<ref name=\"EWFeb97\">{{Cite journal |first=Jim |last=Farber |title=Review: ''Greetings, \"Earthling\"'' |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time, Inc]] |issue=14 February 1997 |page=59}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000892reviews.html |work=[[NME]] |archivedate=17 August 2000 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |last=Mulvey |first=John |title=David Bowie \u2013 Earthling (RCA) |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817212102/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000892reviews.html |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 8.0/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/b/bowie_david/earthling.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001015134723/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/b/bowie_david/earthling.shtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 October 2000|title=David Bowie: Earthling: Pitchfork Review|date=15 October 2000}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Robert Christgau]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating-Christgau|dud}}<ref name=\"Christgau review\">{{Cite web |author=Christgau, Robert |title=Review: ''Earthling (Virgin, 1997)'' |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=david+bowie |accessdate=3 August 2009 |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"rollingstone review\">{{Cite web |author=Kemp, Mark |title=Review: ''Earthling \u2013 David Bowie'' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/7480/37384 |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=5 March 2010 |authorlink=Mark Kemp}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide |year=2004 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|pages=97\u201398|title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide }}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10score = 6/10<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Davis Bowie: Earthling (virgin) |magazine= [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]  |date=March 1997 |last=Salamon |first=Jeff |page=102 }}</ref>\n}}\nThough not a major commercial success, the album scored a number of positive reviews<ref name=Bowie50 /> with one reviewer calling it a \"richly textured\" \"return to excellence\"<ref name=ER>{{Citation| last = Laban| first = Linda| title = Earthling: Substance wins over fashion| newspaper = The Seattle Times| location = Seattle, WA | date = 13 February 1997| page = E3}}</ref> and another saying the album represented \"some of his [Bowie's] finest music in a decade\".<ref name=chicagotribune /> In the 1998 [[Grammy Award]]s ''Earthling'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Performance]] and the song \"[[Dead Man Walking (song)|Dead Man Walking]]\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Rock Vocal Performance|Best Male Rock Vocal Performance]]. The album performed better than its highly experimental predecessor, ''Outside'', reaching No. 6 in the UK charts and No. 39 in the US.<ref name=\"Buckley\">{{Cite book|last=Buckley| first=David|year=2000| origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=Virgin |isbn=978-0-7535-0457-4|pages=517\u2013527, pp.624\u2013625}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine praised the album, noting that exposure to [[Nine Inch Nails]] on Bowie's previous [[Outside Tour|tour]] had apparently influenced him on this album, and they called it \"his best since 1980's ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)|Scary Monsters]]''.\"<ref name=RS754>{{Citation | last=Kemp | first=Mark | title=Earthling Review | journal=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone magazine]] | issue=754 | date=20 February 1997 | pages=65\u201366}}</ref> The album scored a minor hit with a [[Trent Reznor]] [[remix]] of \"[[I'm Afraid of Americans]]\".\n\nA Mandarin version of the song \u2018Seven Years in Tibet\u2019 topped the charts in [[Hong Kong]] marking Bowie as the first non-Asian artist to reach number 1 in that territory.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Billboard Hits Of The World |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 26 July 1997 |volume= 109 |issue= 30 |page= 45 |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lg4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=seven+years+in+tibet+hong+kong+charts&source=bl&ots=iY7aSgt3kq&sig=d6fealoIWn89eSUsWSAAcYwfquI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiY1sKHvf3YAhVGEVAKHTu5BacQ6AEIXDAN#v=onepage&q=Seven%20years%20in%20Tibet  |issn= 0006-2510}}</ref>\n\n==Remixes and music videos==\nBowie's enthusiasm for remixing reached its peak when this album was released and the numerous singles from it were also issued to clubs, as well as online: three versions of \"Telling Lies\" were released on Bowie's official website months prior to the album's release, constituting the first ever [[download]]able single by a major artist.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004| origyear=2000 |title=The Complete David Bowie |location=London |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn | isbn=978-1-903111-73-4}}</ref> \"[[Little Wonder (song)|Little Wonder]]\" was the album's biggest hit, reaching No. 14 in the UK.\n\nThree more singles \u2014 \"Dead Man Walking\", \"Seven Years in Tibet\" and \"I'm Afraid of Americans\" (with participation of [[Trent Reznor]]) \u2014 did not fare so well, although the latter did remain in the US charts for 16 weeks, peaking at No. 66.<ref name=\"Buckley\"/>\n\nThe music videos for ''Earthling'' were elaborate. Artist and director [[Floria Sigismondi]] directed the short films for \"Little Wonder\" and \"Dead Man Walking\", while [[Dom and Nic]] directed \"I'm Afraid of Americans\", the latter being nominated for an [[MTV Video Music Award]]. A video was also made for \"Seven Years in Tibet\", composed largely of concert footage.\n\n==Live performances==\nBowie took songs from this album on the road in September 1996, performing four US east coast \"club\" shows, including one at the [[Roseland Ballroom]] in [[New York City]], to positive reviews. Prior to taking the stage for the shows, Bowie would play his new song (\"Telling Lies\") over the loudspeaker, but as the single was only available for download over the Internet, most fans did not recognize the song. The set list for these shows was similar to the set list he'd use during the upcoming 1997 [[Earthling Tour]].<ref name=RS96X>{{Citation | last=Wiederhorn| first=Jon| title=David Bowie Performance Review | journal=Rolling Stone Magazine | issue=746| date=31 October 1996 | pages=33\u201334}}</ref><ref name=nytr>{{citation | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/16/arts/david-bowie-without-all-the-gadgetry.html | title=David Bowie, Without All the Gadgetry | date=16 September 1996 | first=Neil | last=Strauss | journal=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=29 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 January 1997, the day after he turned 50, Bowie held a 50th birthday concert for himself, performing tracks off the album, as well as a selection of songs from his back catalogue. He played to nearly 15,000 fans at New York's [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref name=p97>{{citation | url=http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/david-bowie-spectacular-and-acclaimed-50th-birthday-concert-to-air-as-a-television-pay-per-view-event/ | title=David Bowie: Spectacular and Acclaimed 50th Birthday Concert to Air as a Television Pay Per View Event | date=28 February 1997 | first=Tresa | last=Schneider | work=MSOPR.COM | accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> Bowie was joined onstage by artists including [[Billy Corgan]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Sonic Youth]], [[Black Francis]], [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] and [[Lou Reed]], to perform many of his songs.<ref name=p97/> Other non-performing guests included [[Beck]], [[Moby]], [[Julian Schnabel]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Charlie Sexton]], [[Fred Schneider]], [[Christopher Walken]], [[Matt Dillon]] and Bowie's wife [[Iman (model)|Iman]]. Artist [[Tony Oursler]] designed some of the artwork for the video backdrop that played behind the band onstage. The event was recorded for a [[pay-per-view]] special commemorating the event,<ref>{{Citation | last=Kemp| first=Mark| title=All The Young Dudes | journal=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone magazine]]| issue=755| date=6 March 1997 | pages=24}}</ref><ref name=DB97>{{citation | url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/earthling-david-bowie-celebrates-50th-birthday-triumphant-sold-out-concert-madison-square | title=Earthling David Bowie Celebrates 50th Birthday With Triumphant Sold-out Concert At Madison Square Garden Before 14,500 Fans | date=23 January 1997 | accessdate=5 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519002427/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/earthling-david-bowie-celebrates-50th-birthday-triumphant-sold-out-concert-madison-square | archive-date=19 May 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> and a portion of the proceeds from the event were donated to the charity [[Save the Children]].<ref name=p97 /> [[Tim Pope]], who had previously worked with Bowie directing his 1987 video for \"[[Time Will Crawl]]\", directed the 50th Anniversary video,<ref name=\"tcdbeu\">{{cite book | title=The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated | last=Pegg | first=Nicholas | date=October 2016 | publisher=Titan Books}}</ref> and [[Duncan Jones]], Bowie's son, was one of the camera operators at the event.<ref>{{cite url | url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/3657581/did-you-know-20-facts-about-david-bowie/ | title=Did you know ... 20 facts about David Bowie | first=Kerrie | last=O'brien | date=11 January 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1997, Bowie performed songs from ''Earthling'' live on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and on ''[[The Tonight Show]]''.<ref name=DB97x>{{citation | url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/david-bowie-launches-new-album-earthling-network-television-appearances-pay-view-concert | title=David Bowie Launches New Album 'earthling' With Network Television Appearances, A Pay-per-view Concert, A National Radio Broadcast, And Star On Hollywood Blvd's Walk Of Fame | date=30 January 1997 | accessdate=5 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109020601/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/david-bowie-launches-new-album-earthling-network-television-appearances-pay-view-concert | archive-date=9 January 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Phoenix Festival]] in July 1997, Bowie and his band played in the Radio 1 Dance tent as \"Tao Jones Index\". They performed in darkness with dry ice and strobe lights. Tao Jones Index was a pun based on Bowie's real name, David Jones, and the 1997 [[Celebrity bond#Bowie bonds|Bowie Bond]] issue (Tao is pronounced \"Dow\", as in [[Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow Jones Index]] from the US stock market).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Singles/PA1997/Title.html|title=Pallas Athena 1997 version|access-date=15 January 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227151211/http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Singles/PA1997/Title.html|archive-date=27 February 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBowie went back on the road in support of this album, with his [[Earthling Tour]] taking place between May 1997 and the end of the year.<ref name=Bowie50 />\n\nSome songs from the album's various live performances were released on the promotional-only album ''[[Earthling in the City]]'' (1997).\n\nBowie had said in mid-1996 that he intended to go into the studio to work on ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]]'''s follow-up album after making the studio album using his touring band first,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SM6O_eChn54 | title=David Bowie \u2013 Interview with Alan Bangs/Loreley Festival 1996|date=June 1996|accessdate=26 November 2018}} [[Alan Bangs]]</ref> but no follow-up to ''Outside'' was ever produced. Bowie's next album was his 1999 album ''[[Hours (David Bowie album)|Hours]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics   = [[David Bowie]]\n| all_music    = Bowie, [[Reeves Gabrels]] and [[Mark Plati]], except where noted\n| title1       = [[Little Wonder (song)|Little Wonder]]\n| length1      = 6:02\n| title2       = Looking for Satellites\n| length2      = 5:21\n| title3       = Battle for Britain (The Letter)\n| length3      = 4:48\n| title4       = Seven Years in Tibet\n| length4      = 6:22\n| music4       = Bowie, Gabrels\n| title5       = [[Dead Man Walking (song)|Dead Man Walking]]\n| length5      = 6:50\n| music5       = Bowie, Gabrels\n| title6       = [[Telling Lies]]\n| length6      = 4:49\n| music6       = Bowie\n| title7       = The Last Thing You Should Do\n| length7      = 4:57\n| title8       = [[I'm Afraid of Americans]]\n| length8      = 5:00\n| music8       = Bowie, [[Brian Eno]]\n| title9       = Law (Earthlings on Fire)\n| length9      = 4:48\n| music9       = Bowie, Gabrels\n| total_length = 48:57\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed    = yes\n| headline     = 2004 reissue bonus tracks\n| extra_column = Remixer(s)\n| title10      = Little Wonder\n| note10       = dance [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]]\n| extra10      = [[Danny Saber]]\n| length10     = 5:34\n| title11      = I'm Afraid of Americans\n| note11       = V1 mix\n| extra11      = [[Nine Inch Nails]] \n| length11     = 5:31\n| title12      = Dead Man Walking\n| note12       = mix 2 US promo 12\"\n| extra12      = [[Moby]]\n| length12     = 5:27\n| title13      = Telling Lies\n| note13       = mix\n| extra13      = [[Adam F]]\n| length13     = 5:09\n| total_length = 21:41 \n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed    = yes\n| headline     = 2004 Digibook expanded edition bonus disc\n| title_width  = 55%\n| lyrics_width = 20%\n| music_width  = 5%\n| extra_width  = 20%\n| extra_column = Remixer(s)\n| title1       = Little Wonder\n| note1        = censored video edit\n| length1      = 4:09\n| title2       = Little Wonder\n| note2        = club mix\n| extra2       = [[Junior Vasquez]]\n| length2      = 8:18\n| title3       = Little Wonder\n| note3        = dance mix\n| extra3       = Danny Saber\n| length3      = 5:34\n| title4       = Seven Years in Tibet\n| note4        = [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] version) ({{zh|c=\u524e\u90a3\u5929\u5730|l=A Fleeting Moment}}\n| lyrics4      = Bowie, <abbr title=\"interpreted by\">intr.</abbr> [[Lin Xi]]\n| length4      = 4:00\n| title5       = Dead Man Walking\n| note5        = mix 1\n| extra5       = Moby\n| length5      = 7:34\n| title6       = Dead Man Walking\n| note6        = mix 2 US promo 12\"\n| extra6       = Moby\n| length6      = 5:27\n| title7       = Telling Lies\n| note7        = Feelgood mix\n| extra7       = Mark Plati\n| length7      = 5:09\n| title8       = Telling Lies\n| note8        = Paradox mix\n| extra8       = [[A Guy Called Gerald]]\n| length8      = 5:10\n| title9       = I'm Afraid of Americans\n| note9        = ''[[Showgirls]]'' [[soundtrack]] version\n| length9      = 5:13\n| title10      = I'm Afraid of Americans\n| note10       = V1 mix\n| extra10      = Nine Inch Nails\n| length10     = 5:31\n| title11      = I'm Afraid of Americans\n| note11       = V1 clean edit\n| extra11      = Nine Inch Nails\n| length11     = 4:14\n| title12      = [[V-2 Schneider]]\n| note12       = Tao Jones Index) (live at the [[Paradiso (Amsterdam)|Paradiso]], [[Amsterdam]], 10 June 1997\n| music12      = Bowie\n| length12     = 7:16\n| title13      = [[Pallas Athena (song)|Pallas Athena]]\n| note13       = Tao Jones Index) (live at the Paradiso, Amsterdam, 10 June 1997\n| music13      = Bowie\n| length13     = 8:20\n| total_length = 76:45 \n}}\n'''Notes'''\n*\"I'm Afraid of Americans\" first appeared in 1995 on the soundtrack for the film ''[[Showgirls (soundtrack)|Showgirls]]'', in a version that was extremely rough compared to the ''Earthling'' recording.\n*Track 13 of the 2004 reissue, unlike the other bonus tracks on it, is not present on the 2004 Digibook expanded edition reissue's bonus disc.\n*Track 11 in the bonus disc for the 2004 Digibook expanded edition is mistakenly labeled as the V1 edit. Apparently, it is an edited album version, which previously only appeared on the 1997 promotional CD \"The Radio Edits\", along with the edits of \"Seven Years in Tibet\" (which was later released as a single) and a unique edit of \"Looking for Satellites\", which has never been released in any other form. Disc 1 in this edition contains a [[pregap]] of 36 seconds of silence between \"Dead Man Walking\" and \"Telling Lies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Album5.htm#Earthling|title=Illustrated DB Discography (Earthling album)|last=Altenburg|first=Ruud|accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Promo4.htm#Radio%20Edits|title=Illustrated DB Discography (The Radio Edits promo CD)|last=Altenburg|first=Ruud|accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref>\n*The project concept for the Mandarin lyric interpretation of the [[Mandarin Chinese|dialect group's]] version of \"Seven Years in Tibet\" comes from [[Anthony Wong (singer)|Elvin Wong]].\n\n==Personnel==\nAdapted from the ''Earthling'' liner notes.<ref name=linernotes>{{cite AV media notes|title=Earthling|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1997|publisher=[[Vigin Records]]|type=CD booklet}}</ref>\n*[[David Bowie]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|vocals]]; [[guitar]]; [[alto saxophone]]; [[sampling (music)|samples]]; [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*[[Reeves Gabrels]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Programming (music)|programming]]; [[Synthesizer|synthesisers]]; real and sampled guitars; vocals\n*[[Mark Plati]]&nbsp;\u2013 programming; [[Loop (music)|loops]]; samples; keyboards\n*[[Gail Ann Dorsey]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]]; vocals\n*[[Zack Alford]] &nbsp;\u2013 drum loops; acoustic [[Drum kit|drums]]; [[Electronic drum|electronic percussion]]\n*[[Mike Garson]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards; [[piano]]\n\n'''Production'''\n*David Bowie&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|producer]]\n*Reeves Gabrels&nbsp;\u2013 producer\n*Mark Plati&nbsp;\u2013 producer; [[audio engineer|engineer]]; [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (1997)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australian [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"auchart\">{{cite web|title=australian-charts.com David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|45\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"atchart\">{{cite web|title= David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling'' \u2013 austriancharts.at|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Belgian Albums Chart (Flanders)<ref name=\"beVlchart\">{{cite web|title= ultratop.be&nbsp;\u2014 David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a|language=Dutch|publisher=Ultratop|work=ultratop.be/nl, Hung Medien|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart (Wallonia)]]<ref name=\"bewachart\">{{cite web|title= ultratop.be&nbsp;\u2014 David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a|language=French|work=ultratop.be/fr,, Hung Medien|publisher=Ultratop|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canadian RPM Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7772&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=adi8sjvtk744tnp1av8s57ktv2|title=Top Albums/CDs \u2013 Volume 64, No. 25, February 24, 1997|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|format=PHP|date=4 February 1997|accessdate=10 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109015320/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7772&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=adi8sjvtk744tnp1av8s57ktv2|archive-date=9 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|21\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Danish Albums ([[Hitlisten]])<ref name=\"Listen\">{{cite news |title=Listen \u2013 Danmarks Officielle Hitliste \u2013 Udarbejdet af AIM Nielsen for IFPI Danmark \u2013 Uge 7 |work=[[Ekstra Bladet]] |location=[[Copenhagen]] |language=Danish |date=1997-02-16 }}</ref>\n|18\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[MegaCharts|Dutch Mega Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"nlchart\">{{cite web|title=dutchcharts.nl David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|work=dutchcharts.nl|publisher=[[MegaCharts]]|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|19\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Finnish Albums Chart<ref name=\"fichart\">{{cite web|title=finnishcharts.com RDavid Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|url=http://finnishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng&cat=a\n|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[SNEP|French SNEP Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"fracharts\">{{cite web|title=lescharts.com David Bowie \u2013 ''Earthling''|work=lescharts.com|publisher=[[SNEP]]|url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Eart+hl+i+ng+In+Hi-Fi&cat=a|language=French|format=ASP|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n|9\n|-\n|align=\"lef