LaMPA]])|artist=David Bowie|award=Gold|title=Earhling|type=album|salesamount=4,000<sup>*</sup>|certref=<ref>{{cite web|title= International Latvian Certification Awards from 1998 to 2001 |publisher= [[Latvian Music Producers Association]] |via= Directupload |year= 1999 |access-date= 13 June 2019 |url= http://www.directupload.net/file/d/4145/cldudhyw_pdf.htm}}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|title=Earthling|artist=David Bowie|type=album|relyear=1997|region=United Kingdom|award=Silver|certyear=2013}}\n{{certification Table Bottom}}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|1990s}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090308032621/http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Reviews/Albums/E/PressRelease.html Teenage Wildlife] hosts the original press release for the album.\n* {{Discogs master|type=album|49746|name=Earthling}}\n\n{{David Bowie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earthling (Album)}}\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mark Plati]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Reeves Gabrels]]\n[[Category:David Bowie albums]]\n", "name_user": "Zmbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLive performances:MOS:ITALICTITLE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earthling_(album)"}
{"title_page": "It (film series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American horror film series}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''It''\n| image = IT (2017 film) logo.svg\n| caption = Official logo, used since the [[It (2017 film)|2017 film]]\n| creator = {{plainlist|\n* [[New Line Cinema]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* [[KatzSmith Productions]]\n}}\n| origin = ''[[It (novel)|It]]''\n| owner = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| films = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two]]''}}\n| soundtracks = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)#Music|It (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two#Music|It Chapter Two (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n| novels = ''It''\n}}\n\n'''''It''''' is a series of American [[horror film]]s. The series consists of two films and is the second adaptation of the [[It (novel)|original novel]] by [[Stephen King]], after [[Tommy Lee Wallace]]'s [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]]. The first installment was the film ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]'', released in 2017 by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The franchise centers around a group of seven children living in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by an [[It (character)|eponymous being]] only to face their own personal demons in the process. This being returns to haunt the children every 27 years. The second installment, ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' follows the group 27 years after the events of the first installment.\n\nThe film series received generally positive critical reception and grossed a combined $1.1{{nbsp}}billion against a combined budget of $114{{nbsp}}million, becoming the [[List of highest-grossing horror films#Top 25 highest-grossing horror film franchises and film series|sixth-highest-grossing horror franchise ever]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"column\" style=\"width:12%\"| Film\n! U.S. release date\n! Director(s)\n! Writer(s)\n! Producer(s)\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#ccccff;\" | Films\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n| September 8, 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Andy Muschietti]]\n| Chase Palmer, [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] & [[Gary Dauberman]]\n| [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], David Katzenberg, [[Roy Lee]], [[Dan Lin]] & [[Barbara Muschietti]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n| September 6, 2019\n| Gary Dauberman\n| Roy Lee, Dan Lin & Barbara Muschietti\n|}\n\n===''It'' (2017)===\n{{Main|It (2017 film)}}\n''It'' (retroactively known as ''It Chapter One'') is a 2017 American [[supernatural horror film]] based on the 1986 [[It (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Stephen King]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Release Date Set by Warner Bros|last=Geier|first=Thom|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=April 22, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024120617/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|archivedate=October 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is the second adaptation of the novel, following a 1990 [[It (miniseries)|television miniseries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|title=It Remake Has a Rating, Plans for a Sequel|last=Staley|first=Brandon|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401143822/http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|archivedate=April 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/03/30/it-how-the-stephen-king-remake-compares-to-the-original-tv-miniseries|title=It: How the Stephen King Remake Compares to the Original TV Miniseries|last=Schedeen|first=Jesse|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> The film tells the story of seven children in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by the eponymous being, only to face their own personal demons in the process. [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] stars as [[Bill Denbrough]], with [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] starring as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]].<ref name=\"Jaeden\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Casts Hollywood Legacy as Pennywise the Clown|last=Verhoeven|first=Beatrice|date=June 2, 2016|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620073324/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|archivedate=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]], [[Sophia Lillis]], [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Chosen Jacobs]], [[Nicholas Hamilton]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Jackson Robert Scott]], and Stephen Bogaert are all featured in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Jaeden\" /> [[Principal photography]] began on June 27, 2016, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa|Oshawa, Ontario]], and [[Riverdale, Toronto]], and ended on September 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|title=Stephen King has an 'It' remake update for you|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=April 13, 2016|work=[[HitFix]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622101005/http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|archivedate=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|title='It' Wraps Production with One Last Creepy Photo|last=Keene|first=Allison|date=September 22, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928204639/http://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|archivedate=September 28, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|title=Mansion in Riverdale sets the scene for horror film 'It'|last=Greenberg|first=Courtney|date=August 15, 2016|work=CTV Toronto|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002055307/http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|archivedate=October 2, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on September 8, 2017 and grossed over $700 million worldwide, against a production budget of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4935221/it-box-office-stephen-king/|title=It Shatters Box Office Records With Massive Opening Weekend|last=Calfas|first=Jennifer|date=September 10, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It is the highest-grossing horror film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/29/stephen-king-it-the-exorcist-highest-grossing-horror-film-ever|title=Stephen King's It scares off The Exorcist to become highest-grossing horror ever|last=Mumford|first=Gwilym|date=September 29, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-it-movie-horror-record-despicable-me-3-kingsman-never-say-die-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202184382/|title=\u2018Blade Runner 2049\u2019 Arrives With $50M Overseas; \u2018It\u2019 Tops $600M WW; \u2018Despicable 3\u2019 Hops Past \u2018Zootopia\u2019 \u2013 Intl Box Office|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=October 8, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It received positive reviews, with critics praising the performances, direction, cinematography and musical score, and many calling it one of the best Stephen King adaptations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-review-roundup-1035698|title='It': What the Critics Are Saying|last=Rahman|first=Abid|date=September 6, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> In addition, the film was named as one of the best films of 2017 by various critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 5, 2017|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''It Chapter Two'' (2019) ===\n{{main|It Chapter Two}}\nTalks for an ''It'' sequel began in February 2016. By September 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that it would be released in September 2019, with Dauberman writing the script and Muschietti to direct. [[Principal photography]] began on June 19, 2018, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa]], and [[Toronto, Ontario]], and wrapped on October 31, 2018. The film is directed by [[Andy Muschietti]] from a screenplay by [[Gary Dauberman]]. Set in 2016, 27 years after the first film, it stars <!-- Do not change; Chastain is top-billed in the film's credits  -->[[Jessica Chastain]], [[James McAvoy]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], [[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]], and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], who returns as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]. ''It Chapter Two'' premiered at the [[Fox Theater, Westwood Village|Regency Village Theater]] in [[Los Angeles]] on August 26, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on September 6, 2019. The film received praise for its acting (particularly Hader and Skarsg\u00e5rd) and themes, though criticism was aimed at its runtime and weaker scares compared to its predecessor. Its faithfulness to the novel also drew a polarized response.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-chapter-two-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1236289|title='It: Chapter Two': What the Critics Are Saying|author=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 3, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Supercut===\nIn September 2019, Muschietti expressed interest in releasing a \"Supercut\" version of both chapters. This version would combine both films into one with scenes that were left in the editing process. Muschietti also mentioned the possibility of adding two or three new scenes that would be shot for this edition. The existing scenes will not be re-edited. Instead, it will play out as extended versions of both films, with an intermission included to separate the two. The future of this version has not yet been announced, as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS4x9uVWOBU&t=405s|title=Director Andy Muschietti tells us why he wants to shoot new scenes for IT |date=September 10, 2019|language=en-US|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Future ===\nIn September 2019, Skarsg\u00e5rd spoke of the possibility of a third installment, saying, \"It would have to be the right type of approach to it. The book ends where the second movie ends, so that is the final chapter of this story. There is this interesting aspect of going back in time before all this happened. There might be a story there that might be worth exploring. Obviously that would be a story that's not in the book, it would be a freestanding story, but obviously within the same universe. So, there might be something interesting out of it. I think it would be fun.\"<ref>https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/08/it-chapter-two-pennywise-bill-skarsgard/</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Dauberman discussed in an interview of the possibility of a third film, saying, \"I do think it's possible. Anything in the Stephen King Universe interests me but there's only so much of the story we could tell in the two movies. There are definitely elements of the novel you could expand on and make its own movie. It's just a question of whether or not people want to see it but I do think It was on this planet for a very, very, very long time and that's a lot of bloodshed and a lot of stories to tell and I think you could do that for sure.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/it-chapter-3-1839759979/amp|title=It Chapter 3: Screenwriter Gary Dauberman Says 'It's Possible'|website=io9.gizmodo.com|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nThe project was in ongoing development since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|title=It's coming, as Hollywood plans Stephen King adaptation|last=Opie|first=David|date=March 13, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019031106/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|archivedate=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|title=The Complete Guide to the 'It' Remake: Stephen King's Pennywise Is Back|last=Dionne|first=Zach|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018085202/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|title=Warner Bros Remaking Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018213742/http://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The proposed film adaptations had gone through two major phases of planning: initially with [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] from 2009 to 2015, with the early contributions of screenwriter [[David Kajganich]], and with [[Andy Muschietti]], with Fukunaga remaining in some capacity due to prior screenplay contributions.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|title=Stephen King's It \u2013 everything you need to know|last=Williams|first=Owen|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=August 11, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925053809/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|archivedate=September 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|title=Updates on the 'Pet Sematary' and 'It' Remakes|last=Schrader|first=Chris|date=July 1, 2010|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018215511/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Getting Two-Film Adaptation by 'Jane Eyre' Director|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=June 8, 2012|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316153624/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|archivedate=March 16, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|title=Cary Fukunaga Explains the Demise of His Unconventional 'IT' Adaptation|last=Fischer|first=Russ|date=September 5, 2015|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214854/http://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== David Kajganich (2009\u20132010) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The thing about Stephen King's writing is that he draws his characters so well, it's hard not to imagine they're real people. So it honestly didn't occur to me to try to think of actors in those roles. Pennywise is a bit of a different story, though. His manner is so crucial to what's frightening about him, and it's too much fun to imagine all of the nuances different actors could give him. I think there are a hundred actors who could each pull off a fascinating, horrifying Pennywise, and I tried not to get too attached to any one actor in my head. I think the Pennywise in this adaptation is a less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality than was [[Tim Curry]]'s Pennywise. I think it will be harder to laugh at his antics since, under the permissiveness of an R rating, I was able to give him back a lot of his more upsetting moments from the novel, ones that could never be aired on network television.\"\n| source = David Kajganich, on the construction of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 INTERVIEW|last=Lilja's Library Editors|first=|work=Lilja's Library|date=June 29, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n}}On March 12, 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] would be bringing [[Stephen King]]'s novel to the big screen, with David Kajganich to adapt King's novel, while Dan Lin, [[Roy Lee]] and Doug Davison would be producing the piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|title=Warner Bros. taps Kajganich for 'It'|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719080933/http://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|archivedate=July 19, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> When Kajganich learned of Warner Bros.' plans to adapt King's novel, he went after the job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 Interview|last=Lilja's Library Editor|first=|date=June 29, 2010|work=Lilja's Library|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808234208/http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Knowing that Warner Bros. was committed to adapting ''It'' as a single feature film, Kajganich began to attempt to try to find a structure that would accommodate such a large number of characters in two different time periods, around 120 pages, which was one of Warner Bros.' stipulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Screenwriter Gives Update on Big Screen Adaptation of Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524144215/http://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich worked with Lin, Lee, and Davison on ''[[The Invasion (film)|The Invasion]]'' (2007), and he knew they would champion good storytelling, and allow him the time to work out a solid first draft of the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|title=Stephen King's \"It\" Bound For Big Screen|last=Castina|first=|date=July 6, 2010|work=PopCrunch|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815153332/http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|archivedate=August 15, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich spoke of the remake being set in the, \"mid-1980s and in the present mirroring the twenty-odd-year gap King uses in the book and with a great deal of care and attention paid to the backstories of all the characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|title=Exclusive: More on the IT Remake! Rated R?|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804120207/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKajganich also mentioned that Warner Bros. wished for the adaptation to be rated R which he furthered by saying, \"we can really honor the book and engage with the traumas that these characters endure.\", while Kajganich spoke of Warner Bros. wanting the adaptation as a single film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|title=Remake of Stephen King's It will be Rated-R and Set in the Mid-1980s|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829002848/http://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|archivedate=August 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 29, 2010, the screenplay was being re-written by Kajganich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|title=Early Details on the IT Remake|last=Serafini|first=Matt|date=June 30, 2010|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808233147/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said that his dream choice for Pennywise would be [[Buster Keaton]] if he were still alive, and the Pennywise that Kajganich scripted being \"less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|title=SCREENWRITER DAVID KAJGANICH GIVES AN UPDATE ON STEPHEN KING'S IT|last=Stephens|first=Niki|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804190540/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Cary Fukunaga (2012\u20132015) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"I am in the midst of rewriting the first script now.  We're not working on the second part yet. The first script is just about the kids. It's more like ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) meets a horror film. We're definitely honoring the spirit of Stephen King, but the horror has to be modernized to make it relevant. That's my job, right now, on this pass. I'm working on making the horror more about suspense than visualization of any creatures. I just don't think that's scary. What could be there, and the sounds and how it interacts with things, is scarier than actual monsters.\"\n| source = \u2013 Cary Fukunaga, on the development of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|title=Director Cary Fukunaga Talks TRUE DETECTIVE, Making an 8-Hour Film, Future Seasons, BEASTS OF NO NATION, Modernizing Horror with IT, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|work=[[Collider.com]]|date=January 11, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807054534/http://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On June 7, 2012, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  had revealed that Cary Fukunaga was boarding the project as director and will co-write the script with Chase Palmer, while Roy Lee and Dan Lin are producing, as with [[Seth Grahame-Smith]] and David Katzenberg of KatzSmith Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Be Adapted by Cary Fukunaga into Two Films (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=June 7, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706192550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|archivedate=July 6, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, Warner Bros. was announced to have moved the film to its [[New Line Cinema]] division, with overseer duties conducting by New Line's Walter Hamada and Dave Neustadter, along with Vice President of Production at Warner Bros., Niija Kuykendall.<ref name=New>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|title=Stephen King's 'It' Moves From Warner Bros. to New Line (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730140142/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|archivedate=July 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 5, 2014, in an interview with ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'', Dan Lin announced that the first film will be a [[coming-of-age]] story about the children tormented by [[It (character)|It]] and the second will skip ahead in time as those same characters band together to continue the fight as adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|title=Stephen King's IT Will Shoot Next Summer|last=Evry|first=Max|date=December 5, 2014|work=Coming Soon|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172056/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|archivedate=March 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin also stated that Fukunaga was only committed to directing the first film, though was currently closing a deal to co-write the second. Lin concluded by mentioning King, to which he remarked, \"The most important thing is that [King] gave us his blessing. We didn't want to make this unless he felt it was the right way to go, and when we sent him the script, the response that Cary got back was, 'Go with God, please! This is the version the studio should make.' So that was really gratifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/12/fukunaga-to-shoot-stephen-kings-it-next-summer.html?mid=twitter_vulture#|title=Cary Fukunaga Will Shoot Stephen King's It Next Summer|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|date=December 5, 2014|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> Lin confirmed that Fukunaga would begin [[principal photography]] in Summer 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|title=Stephen King's It remake put on indefinite hold as director Cary Fukunaga walks out|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007150949/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|archivedate=October 7, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Fukunaga was interviewed by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wherein he spoke about ''It'', while mentioning he has someone in mind for the role of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|title=Cary Fukunaga on Adapting It, His Musical With Owen Pallett, and #TrueDetectiveSeason2|last=Wickman|first=Forrest|date=February 3, 2015|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628135946/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 3, 2015, Fukunaga spoke of the film, particularly noting his goal to find the \"perfect guy to play Pennywise\". Fukunaga also revealed that he, Kajganich and Palmer had changed the names and dates in the script, adding, the spirit is similar to what he'd like to see in cinemas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|title='It' Director Seeks \"Perfect Pennywise\" Clown|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=March 3, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624183418/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 4, 2015, it was officially announced that [[Will Poulter]] had been cast to play Pennywise, after Fukunaga was \"blown away\" by his audition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|title=Will Poulter cast as Pennywise in Cary Fukunaga's It|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618220510/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|archivedate=June 18, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WillP\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|title=Will Poulter to Play the Evil Clown in 'It' Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629051959/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ty Simpkins]] was considered to play one of The Losers' Club members.<ref name=\"Ty\">{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|title=Jurassic World Interview with Ty Simpkins|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=February 27, 2016|work=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025114439/http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|archivedate=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2015, it was reported that Fukunaga had dropped out as the director of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|title='It' Loses Director Cary Fukunaga|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709011956/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|archivedate=July 9, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to [[TheWrap]], Fukunaga clashed with the studio and didn't want to compromise his artistic vision in the wake of budget cuts by New Line, which greenlit the first film at $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|title=Cary Fukunaga Out as Director of Stephen King's 'It' at New Line (Exclusive)|last=Geier|first=Thom|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628034157/https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Fukunaga maintained that wasn't the case, with him stating he had bigger disagreements with New Line over the direction of the story: \"I was trying to make an unconventional horror film. It didn't fit into the algorithm of what they knew they could spend and make money back on based on not offending their standard genre audience.\"<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|title=Cary Fukunaga Offers New Details on Why 'It' Remake Fell Apart|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|date=September 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704095044/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|archivedate=July 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He made mention that the budget was perfectly fine, as well as his desire to make Pennywise more than just the clown.<ref name=\"Cary\" /> Fukunaga concluded by stating, \"We invested years and so much anecdotal storytelling in it. Chase and I both put our childhood in that story. So our biggest fear was they were going to take our script and bastardize it So I'm actually thankful that they are going to rewrite the script. I wouldn't want them to stealing our childhood memories and using that I was honoring King's spirit of it, but I needed to update it. King saw an earlier draft and liked it.\"<ref name=\"Cary\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|title=Cary Fukunaga opens up about IT departure \u2013 Exclusive|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=August 17, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108110348/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|archivedate=November 8, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On Fukunaga's departure, King wrote, \"The remake of ''IT'' may be dead or undead but we'll always have [[Tim Curry]]. He's still floating down in the sewers of Derry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/602931191281496064|title=The remake of IT may be dead|last=King|first=Stephen|date=May 25, 2015|work=Twitter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322192030/https://twitter.com/StephenKing/status/602931191281496064|archivedate=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|title=It Remake 'Dead' As Director Walks Away|last=Sky News Editors|first=Justin|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[Sky News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528215629/http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|archivedate=May 28, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Andy Muschietti (2015\u20132017) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The way Cary intended to execute the script is something that only he can talk about. I can say my version of ''It'' highly emphasizes Pennywise's most terrifying virtue, which is It's ability to materialise into your worse fear; I want to take people in a journey into Pennywise's world through a disturbing, surrealistic and intoxicating experience that will leave nobody at ease.\"\n| source = \u2013 Andy Muschietti, on his version of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|title=IT Emphasizes Pennywise's Most Terrifying Virtue|last=Jorissen|first=Matt|work=Lilja's Library|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808225514/http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On July 16, 2015, it was announced that Andy Muschietti was in negotiations to direct ''It'', with New Line beginning a search for a new writer to tailor a script to Muschietti's vision,<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|title=Stephen King's 'It' Finds New Director (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 16, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716124053/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|archivedate=July 16, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|title=Mama's Andr\u00e9s Muschietti in Negotiations To Direct It|last=White|first=James|date=July 17, 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003180808/http://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|archivedate=October 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the announcement also confirming the possible participation of Muschietti's sister, Barbara Muschietti, as a producer, and Richard Brener joining Hamada, Neustadter and Kuykendall to oversee the project.<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\" /> On April 22, 2016, it was indicated that Will Poulter, who was originally tapped to portray Pennywise in Fukunaga's version, had dropped out of the film due to a scheduling conflict and that executives were meeting with actors to portray the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 22, 2016, New Line Cinema set the film for a release of September 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|title=Warner Bros. Sets 'CHiPs', 'It' & Untitled PG-13 Comedy For 2017|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624041157/http://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 30, 2015, Muschietti was interviewed by ''Variety'' wherein he spoke about his vision of ''It'', while mentioning Poulter was still in the mix for the role of Pennywise: \"[Poulter] would be a great option. For me he is at the top of my list\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|title=Muschiettis to Produce Supernatural Thriller 'Shadows' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Mayorga|first=Emilio|date=October 30, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305002513/http://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|archivedate=March 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He confirmed that next summer is the time for them to start shooting. It was decided to shoot ''It'' during the summer months to give them the time to work with the children who have the main roles in the first part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Filming Starts Next Summer on Remake of Stephen King Classic 'It'|last=Sewell|first=Annie|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[Inquisitr]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519230246/http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 19, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti went on to say that \"King described 50s' terror iconography,\" adding that he feels there is a whole world now to \"rediscover, to update.\" He said there won't be any mummies or werewolves and that the \"terrors are going to be a lot more surprising.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Film Next Summer!|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=October 31, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705165415/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|archivedate=July 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 19, 2016, at the [[D.I.C.E. Summit|D.I.C.E. Summit 2016]] producer Roy Lee confirmed that Fukunaga and Chase Palmer's original script had been rewritten, with Lee remarking, \"It will hopefully be shooting later this year. We just got the California tax credit Dauberman wrote the most recent draft working with [Muscetti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|title=Stephen King's It May Start Filming in 2016; Two Movies Still Planned|last=Jones|first=Mike|date=February 19, 2016|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625070804/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, in an interview with [[Collider.com]], David Kajganich expressed uncertainty as to whether drafts of his original screenplay would be used by Dauberman and Muschietti,<ref name=\"Kajganich\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|title='A Bigger Splash' Writer David Kajganich on His Unique Approach to the Remake and 'It'|last=Page|first=Aubrey|date=May 5, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710194841/http://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|archivedate=July 10, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the writer stating, \"We know there's a new director, I don't know myself whether he's going back to any of the previous drafts or writing from scratch. I may not know until the film comes out. I don't know how it works! If you find out let me know.\"<ref name=\"Kajganich\" />\n\nOn June 2, 2016, [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] was confirmed to be portraying lead protagonist, Bill Denbrough.<ref name=\"William\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|title='It' Remake to Star 'Midnight Special's\u2019 Jaeden Lieberher|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204208/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|archivedate=July 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] was in final negotiations to star as Pennywise, whose cast will also include [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Chosen Jacobs]] and [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622160247/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|archivedate=June 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, there was a call for 100 background performers, with the background actor call going from 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. and by 4 p.m. more than 300 people had gone through; the casting call also asked for a marching band and period cars between 1970 and 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope//|title=Hundreds turn up for Stephen King's 'It' background actor cast call in Port Hope|last=Northumberland News Editor|first=|date=June 2, 2016|work=Northumberland News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707232022/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope/|archivedate=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that Owen Teague was set to portray Patrick Hocksetter.<ref name=Hockstetter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|title='Bloodline' Actor Joins Adaptation of Stephen King's 'It' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619100458/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|archivedate=June 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, it was officially announced that [[Nicholas Hamilton]] had been cast to play Henry Bowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|title=Nicholas Hamilton in Stephen King's 'It'; Monterey Media Acquires 'The Last Film Festival'|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=June 21, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626085111/http://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Javier Botet]] was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Horror Wizard Javier Botet to Haunt 'The Mummy' and Stephen King's 'It'|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=June 21, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030644/http://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Creature Performer Javier Botet Joins The Mummy and Stephen King's It|last=Squires|first=John|date=June 22, 2016|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623161735/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 23, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 22, 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Muschietti had chosen actress [[Sophia Lillis]] to portray Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Beverly\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|title=Sophia Lillis Joins New Line's 'It' Remake; Aunjanue Ellis Sign on To Christine Crokos' \u2018Pimp'|last=A. Lincoln|first=Ross|date=June 22, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627162517/http://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|archivedate=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 24, 2016, [[Moviepilot]] reported that Stephen Bogaert was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced, with Bogaert portraying Al Marsh, the abusive father of Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Bogaert\">{{cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|title=Here's The Full Cast List for the New 'IT' Movie|last=Richardson|first=Jancy|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Moviepilot]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629070642/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Barbara Muschietti was interviewed by ''Northumberland News''{{'}} Karen Longwell, wherein she spoke about the filming locations on ''It'', while mentioning the beauty of Port Hope being one of the reasons as to why it was chosen, while Muschietti added, \"We were looking for an idyllic town, one that would be a strong contrast to the story. Port Hope is the kind of place we all wish we had grown up in: long summers riding bicycles, walks by the lake, a lovely main street, charming homes with green lawns, warm people.\"<ref name=Criss>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p|title=Barbara Muschietti, producer of film based on Stephen King's novel 'It', talks about experience in Port Hope|last=Longwell|first=Karen|work=Northumberland News|date=July 22, 2016|accessdate=July 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725134239/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p/|archivedate=July 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti also mentioned that 360 extras from the area, from adults to tiny kids, had been involved.<ref name=\"Criss\" />\n\nOn August 11, 2016, at [[The CW]] [[TCA Awards|TCA]] presentation for the upcoming series ''[[Frequency (TV series)|Frequency]]'', producer Dan Lin spoke of the piece's comparison to [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things (TV series)|Stranger Things]]'', with Lee describing ''It'' being a \"homage to 80s movies\", while remarking: \"I think a great analogy is actually Stranger Things, and we're seeing it on Netflix right now. It's very much an homage to '80s movies, whether it's classic Stephen King or even [[Steven Spielberg|Spielberg]]. Think about ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'' (1986) as far as the bonding amongst the kids. But there is a really scary element in Pennywise.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|title='It' Producer Dan Lin Says the Remake Is Like 'Stranger Things'|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=August 11, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812183907/http://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|archivedate=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin continued, speaking of how well the young cast has bonded in these first weeks of shooting. Lin stated, \"We clearly had a great dynamic amongst the kids. Really great chemistry is always a challenging thing with a movie like It because you're casting kids who don't have a ton of experience, but it ended up being really natural. Each kid, like a ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) or ''Stand by Me'' (1986), has a very specific personality and they're forming the loser's club obviously We've spent a few months getting the kids to bond and now they're going to fight this evil, scary clown.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\" />\n\nOn February 9, 2017, at the press day for ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), Lin confirmed that ''It'' is going to be rated R by the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], to which  he stated to Collider.com{{'}}s Steve Weintraub, \"If you're going to make a \"Rated-R movie\", you have to fully embrace what it is, and you have to embrace the source material. It is a scary clown that's trying to kill kids. They do have a scary clown that's taken over the town of Derry, so it's going to be rated R.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|title=Producer Dan Lin Confirms \u2018It\u2019 Rating and Sequel Plans|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=February 9, 2017|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313125903/http://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, Muschietti, at the [[SXSW]] festival, spoke of an element of the [[pre-production]] phase in his attempt to keep Skarsg\u00e5rd separated from the film's child actors, wherein the actor wasn't introduced to the young cast until Pennywise's first encounter with the children:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|title=SXSW 2017: Impressions of First Footage from IT & New Footage from ANNABELLE 2|last=Wixson|first=Heather|date=March 12, 2017|work=Daily Dead|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313131627/http://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"It was something that we agreed on, and that's how it happened The day that he showed up on the stage, they fucking freaked out. Bill is like, seven-foot high, and I can't describe how scary he looks in person. He's a wiry man, crouching, making sounds, snotting, drooling, speaking in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] sometimes. Terrifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|title=The new Pennywise terrified the young cast of Stephen King\u2019s IT reboot|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312200748/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti stated that the story had been moved forward, with the scenes with the young Losers Club shifting from the 1950s to the 1980s, while also describing their plot as \"getting much wider,\" with new material not in the novel or the [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]].<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|title=SXSW Panel: Face Your Fears|last=Whittaker|first=Richard|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312102610/http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Muschietti said he hoped it would still strike the same emotional resonance that the book did for him when he first read it: \"It's all about trying to hit the core and the heart.\"<ref name=\"SXSW\" />\n\nOn July 12, 2017, Muschietti, in an interview with French magazine ''Mad Movies'', spoke of when developing the R rated film, in which allowed him to go into very adult themes, which was championed from the people at New Line Cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mad-movies.com/fr/module/99999735/4495/ca-d-andy-muschietti|title=\u00c7A BY ANDY MUSCHIETTI|last=Mad Movies Editors|first=|date=July 12, 2017|work=Mad Movies|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|title=New Pennywise Image Found On French Magazine Cover|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 3, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704024519/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|archivedate=July 4, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also stated that, \"if you aimed for a PG-13 movie, you had nothing at the end. So we were very lucky that the producers didn't try to stop us. In fact it's more our own moral compass that sometimes showed us that some things lead us in places where we didn't want to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|title=Andy Muschietti Talks Holding Nothing Back for \"R\"-rated \u2018IT\u2019|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716093735/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/07/it-director-andy-muschietti-on-the-films-r-rating/|title=It director Andy Muschietti on the film\u2019s R rating|last=Collinson|first=Gary|date=July 16, 2017|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the same interview, on July 12, 2017, producer Barbara Muschietti added that there was only one scene that was deemed to be too horrific to feature in the new adaptation, in which she stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unilad.co.uk/film/new-it-film-will-contain-scenes-too-intense-for-the-original/|title=New IT Film Will Contain Scenes \u2018Too Intense\u2019 For The Original|last=Murray|first=Emily|date=July 16, 2017|work=[[UniLad]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> \"you won't find the scene where a kid has his back broken and is thrown in the toilets. We thought that the visual translation of that scene had something that was really too much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|title=The New 'IT' Movie Will Be \"R\" Rated With \"Very Adult Themes\"|last=Naylor|first=Daisy|date=July 16, 2017|work=thehooknew|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808035223/http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/director-muschetti-talks-advantages-r-rating/|title=IT Director Talks the Advantages of an R Rating|last=Carptenter|first=Michael|date=July 16, 2017|work=iHorror|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti concluded by emphasizing that nothing was removed from the original vision, nor was the violence of any event watered down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|title=IT Director: R Rating Allows Film to Explore \u2018Very Adult Themes\u2019|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717232034/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|archivedate=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, in an interview with ''Variety''{{'}}s Brent Lang, director Muschietti commented of the monstrous forms that It shall be taking, as well as noting the fact that they'll be very different from the incarnations present in King's story, in which he stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|title=Various Monsters in \u2018IT\u2019 Will Be Very Different from the Book|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720010749/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"The story is the same, but there are changes in the things the kids are scared of. In the book they're children in the 50s, so the incarnations of the monsters are mainly from movies, so it's [[Larry Talbot|Wolf Man]], [[Imhotep (The Mummy)|the Mummy]], [[Frankenstein's monster|Frankenstein]], and [[Count Dracula|Dracula]]. I had a different approach. I wanted to bring out deeper fears, based not only on movie monsters but on childhood traumas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/director-says-stephen-king-s-it-will-not-feature-the-classic-movie-monsters-641|title=ANDY MUSCHIETTI TALKS IT PART 2 & CLASSIC MOVIE MONSTERS|last=Sprague|first=Mike|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|title=There's new terrifying details about the IT film|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Joe (website)|Joe]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720120650/https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> While on the topic of what being the key to a successful horror film, Muschietti concluded by remarking that \"Stay true to what scares you. If you don't respect that, you can't scare anyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|title=\u2018It\u2019 Director on Tackling the Two R-Rated Movies and Why He Picked Bill Skarsgard for Pennywise|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719214312/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|archivedate=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti explained how Skarsg\u00e5rd caught his attention to embody Pennywise, while pointing out that he didn't want the young cast to spend too much time with the actor when not shooting, and encouraged the cast to \"maintain distance\" between them, wherein Muschietti detailed:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-sequel-1075855.html|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=Female First Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=Female First|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=MSN Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[MSN]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808033345/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> We wanted to carry the impact of the encounters to when the cameras were rolling. The first scene where Bill interacted with the children, it was fun to see how the plan worked. The kids were really, really creeped out by Bill. He's pretty intimidating because he's six-four and has all this makeup.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/movies/2017/07/19/stephen-kings-it-remake-pennywise-bill-skarasgard/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Director Explains How Bill Skarsgard Won Coveted Pennywise Role|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=July 19, 2017|work=Pop Culture|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2016, producer [[Roy Lee]], in an interview with Collider, mentioned a second ''It'' film, remarking, \"[Dauberman] wrote the most recent draft working with [Muschietti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref name=\"Muschietti\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|title=Exclusive: 'It' Movie Hopefully Shooting This Year; Will Be Rated-R|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=February 19, 2016|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626211828/http://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, Muschietti revealed that production was set to begin in the spring of 2018, adding,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti Says He's Coming Back for a Sequel|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720053246/http://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|title=Second IT Movie Adaptation Aims to Start Filming Next Year|last=Zinski|first=Dan|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721010304/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"We'll probably have a script for the second part in January [2018]. Ideally, we would start prep in March. Part one is only about the kids. Part two is about these characters 27 years later as adults, with flashbacks to 1989 when they were kids.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|title=STEPHEN KING'S IT ALREADY HAS A SEQUEL PLANNED|last=Wax|first=Alyse|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Syfy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720065345/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 21, 2017, Muschietti spoke of looking forward to having a dialogue in the second film that does not exist within the first, stating, \"... it seems like we're going to do it. It's the second half, it's not a sequel. It's the second half and it's very connected to the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-andy-muschietti-interview-sdcc/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti on Reinventing Pennywise and Sequel Plans|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 21, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1683730/why-the-it-movie-left-the-adult-storyline-out-of-the-first-film|title=Why The IT Movie Left The Adult Storyline Out Of The First Film|last=O'Connell|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2017|work=CinemaBlend|accessdate=July 23, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti stated that two cut scenes from the first film will possibly be included in the second, one of which being the fire at the Black Spot from the book.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-cut-scenes|title=The 'IT' Movie Had to Cut Two Crazy Scenes to Stay On-Budget|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 27, 2017|work=Collider.com|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that the sequel would be released on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-movie-sequel-release-date-1202570309/|title='It' Sequel Sets September 2019 Release Date|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Variety.com]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> with [[Gary Dauberman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-sequel-plans-moving-forward-at-new-line-1035456|title='It' Movie Sequel Plans Move Forward at New Line|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=September 7, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and Jeffrey Jurgensen (who later went uncredited)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/are-you-afraid-of-the-dark-movie-release-1202632308/|title=''Are You Afraid Of The Dark?'' Movie Gets October 2019 Release|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=Variety|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref> writing the script. Andy Muschietti returned to direct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-sequel-official-writer-gary-dauberman-1202550077/|title='It' Sequel Moves Ahead With Screenwriter Gary Dauberman|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|date=September 7, 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref> Dauberman would later leave the project to write and direct ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]'', while [[Jason Fuchs]] was brought in as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |url=https://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|title=''It 2'' Filmmakers on How Jason Fuchs Helped Bring the Sequel Script to the Finish Line |date=July 22, 2019 |work=Collider |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916055021/http://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Recurring cast and characters ==\n{{Cast indicator|A|C|O|V|Y}}\n<!--Only put characters that have a roles within both films.-->{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Characters\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center:\" |Films\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2017\n! scope=\"col\" |2019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[It (character)|It / Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Bill Denbrough]]\n|[[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]]\n|[[James McAvoy]]<hr>Jaeden Lieberher{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Beverly Marsh]]\n|[[Sophia Lillis]]\n|[[Jessica Chastain]]<hr>Sophia Lillis{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Hanscom\n|[[Jeremy Ray Taylor]]\n|[[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]]<hr>Jeremy Ray Taylor{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Richie Tozier]]\n|[[Finn Wolfhard]]\n|[[Bill Hader]]<hr>Finn Wolfhard{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eddie Kaspbrak]]\n|[[Jack Dylan Grazer]]\n|[[James Ransone]]<hr>Jack Dylan Grazer{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Stanley Uris\n|[[Wyatt Oleff]]\n|[[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]]<hr>Wyatt Oleff{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mike Hanlon\n|[[Chosen Jacobs]]\n|[[Isaiah Mustafa]]<hr>Chosen Jacobs{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Tristian Levi Cox{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Torian Matthew{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Henry Bowers\n|[[Nicholas Hamilton]]\n|Teach Grant<hr>Nicholas Hamilton{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Georgie Denbrough]]\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jackson Robert Scott]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patrick Hockstetter\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Owen Teague]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alvin Marsh \n|colspan=\"2\"| Stephen Bogaert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sonia Kaspbrak / Myra\n|colspan=\"2\"| Molly Atkinson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mr. Keene\n|colspan=\"2\"| Joe Bostick\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Gretta Keene\n|[[Megan Charpentier]]\n|Juno Rinaldi<hr>Megan Charpentier{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |The Hobo / The Leper /<br>The Witch\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Javier Botet]]\n|}\n\n== Additional crew and production details ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Role\n! colspan=\"2\" |Films\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n!2017\n!2019\n|-\n!Composer(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n|-\n!Cinematography\n|[[Chung Chung-hoon|Chung-hoon Chung]]\n|Checco Varese\n|-\n!Editor(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jason Ballantine]]\n|-\n!Production company\n|[[New Line Cinema]]<hr>[[RatPac-Dune Entertainment]]<hr>[[Vertigo Entertainment]]<hr>Lin Pictures<hr>[[KatzSmith Productions]]\n|New Line Cinema<hr>Double Dream<hr>Vertigo Entertainment<hr>Rideback\n|-\n!Distributor\n| colspan=\"8\" |[[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n|-\n!Running time\n|135 minutes\n|170 minutes\n|-\n!Release date\n|{{start date|2017|9|8}}\n|{{start date|2019|9|6}}\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Box office performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;&quot;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" |Box office gross\n! colspan=\"2\" |Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n!North America\n!Other territories\n!Worldwide\n!North America\n!Worldwide\n|-\n|''It''\n|September 8, 2017\n|$327,481,748\n|$372,900,000\n|$700,381,748\n|#66\n|#117\n|$35 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=it.htm|title=It (2017) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|''It Chapter Two''\n|September 6, 2019\n|$211,593,228\n|$260,500,000\n|$472,093,228\n|#190\n|#249\n|$79 million\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1107461633/|title=It: Chapter Two \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Totals\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:327481748+211593228}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:372900000+260500000}}}}\n!${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:700381748+472093228}}}}\n!\n!\n!$114 million\n!\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Film\n![[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n![[Metacritic]]\n![[CinemaScore]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It''\n|86% (368 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_2017|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|69 (49 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/|title=Home|website=Cinemascore|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |''It Chapter Two''\n|63% (353 reviews)<ref>{{Citation|title=It Chapter Two (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/it_chapter_two|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|58 (52 critics)<ref>{{Citation|title=It: Chapter Two|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/it-chapter-two|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n|B+<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Stephen King's It}}\n{{Media based on Stephen King works}}\n\n[[Category:Horror film series]]\n[[Category:It (novel)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American horror film series}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''It''\n| image = IT (2017 film) logo.svg\n| caption = Official logo, used since the [[It (2017 film)|2017 film]]\n| creator = {{plainlist|\n* [[New Line Cinema]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* [[KatzSmith Productions]]\n}}\n| origin = ''[[It (novel)|It]]''\n| owner = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| films = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two]]''}}\n| soundtracks = * {{nowrap|''[[It (2017 film)#Music|It (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[It Chapter Two#Music|It Chapter Two (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)]]''}}\n| novels = ''It''\n}}\n\n'''''It''''' is a series of American [[horror film]]s. The series consists of two films and is the second adaptation of the [[It (novel)|original novel]] by [[Stephen King]], after [[Tommy Lee Wallace]]'s [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]]. The first installment was the film ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]'', released in 2017 by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. The franchise centers around a group of seven children living in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by an [[It (character)|eponymous being]] only to face their own personal demons in the process. This being returns to haunt the children every 27 years. The second installment, ''[[It Chapter Two]]'' follows the group 27 years after the events of the first installment.\n\nThe film series grossed a combined $1.1{{nbsp}}billion against a combined budget of $114{{nbsp}}million, and becoming the [[List of highest-grossing horror films#Top 25 highest-grossing horror film franchises and film series|sixth-highest-grossing horror franchise ever]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"column\" style=\"width:12%\"| Film\n! U.S. release date\n! Director(s)\n! Writer(s)\n! Producer(s)\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:#ccccff;\" | Films\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n| September 8, 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Andy Muschietti]]\n| Chase Palmer, [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] & [[Gary Dauberman]]\n| [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], David Katzenberg, [[Roy Lee]], [[Dan Lin]] & [[Barbara Muschietti]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n| September 6, 2019\n| Gary Dauberman\n| Roy Lee, Dan Lin & Barbara Muschietti\n|}\n\n===''It'' (2017)===\n{{Main|It (2017 film)}}\n''It'' (retroactively known as ''It Chapter One'') is a 2017 American [[supernatural horror film]] based on the 1986 [[It (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Stephen King]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Release Date Set by Warner Bros|last=Geier|first=Thom|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=April 22, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024120617/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-release-date-set-by-warner-bros/|archivedate=October 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is the second adaptation of the novel, following a 1990 [[It (miniseries)|television miniseries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|title=It Remake Has a Rating, Plans for a Sequel|last=Staley|first=Brandon|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401143822/http://www.cbr.com/stephen-king-it-rating-sequel-plans/|archivedate=April 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/03/30/it-how-the-stephen-king-remake-compares-to-the-original-tv-miniseries|title=It: How the Stephen King Remake Compares to the Original TV Miniseries|last=Schedeen|first=Jesse|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 9, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> The film tells the story of seven children in [[Derry (Stephen King)|Derry, Maine]], who are terrorized by the eponymous being, only to face their own personal demons in the process. [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] stars as [[Bill Denbrough]], with [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] starring as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]].<ref name=\"Jaeden\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Casts Hollywood Legacy as Pennywise the Clown|last=Verhoeven|first=Beatrice|date=June 2, 2016|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620073324/http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-kings-it-casts-hollywood-legacy-as-pennywise-the-clown/|archivedate=June 20, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]], [[Sophia Lillis]], [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Chosen Jacobs]], [[Nicholas Hamilton]], [[Owen Teague]], [[Jackson Robert Scott]], and Stephen Bogaert are all featured in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Jaeden\" /> [[Principal photography]] began on June 27, 2016, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa|Oshawa, Ontario]], and [[Riverdale, Toronto]], and ended on September 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|title=Stephen King has an 'It' remake update for you|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=April 13, 2016|work=[[HitFix]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622101005/http://www.hitfix.com/the-dartboard/stephen-king-has-an-it-remake-update-for-you|archivedate=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|title='It' Wraps Production with One Last Creepy Photo|last=Keene|first=Allison|date=September 22, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928204639/http://collider.com/it-movie-wraps-production/|archivedate=September 28, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|title=Mansion in Riverdale sets the scene for horror film 'It'|last=Greenberg|first=Courtney|date=August 15, 2016|work=CTV Toronto|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002055307/http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/mansion-in-riverdale-sets-the-scene-for-horror-film-it-1.3029802|archivedate=October 2, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film was released on September 8, 2017 and grossed over $700 million worldwide, against a production budget of $35 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4935221/it-box-office-stephen-king/|title=It Shatters Box Office Records With Massive Opening Weekend|last=Calfas|first=Jennifer|date=September 10, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It is the highest-grossing horror film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/29/stephen-king-it-the-exorcist-highest-grossing-horror-film-ever|title=Stephen King's It scares off The Exorcist to become highest-grossing horror ever|last=Mumford|first=Gwilym|date=September 29, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/blade-runner-2049-it-movie-horror-record-despicable-me-3-kingsman-never-say-die-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202184382/|title=\u2018Blade Runner 2049\u2019 Arrives With $50M Overseas; \u2018It\u2019 Tops $600M WW; \u2018Despicable 3\u2019 Hops Past \u2018Zootopia\u2019 \u2013 Intl Box Office|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=October 8, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> It received positive reviews, with critics praising the performances, direction, cinematography and musical score, and many calling it one of the best Stephen King adaptations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-review-roundup-1035698|title='It': What the Critics Are Saying|last=Rahman|first=Abid|date=September 6, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> In addition, the film was named as one of the best films of 2017 by various critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 5, 2017|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''It Chapter Two'' (2019) ===\n{{main|It Chapter Two}}\nTalks for an ''It'' sequel began in February 2016. By September 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that it would be released in September 2019, with Dauberman writing the script and Muschietti to direct. [[Principal photography]] began on June 19, 2018, at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] and on locations in and around [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], [[Oshawa]], and [[Toronto, Ontario]], and wrapped on October 31, 2018. The film is directed by [[Andy Muschietti]] from a screenplay by [[Gary Dauberman]]. Set in 2016, 27 years after the first film, it stars <!-- Do not change; Chastain is top-billed in the film's credits  -->[[Jessica Chastain]], [[James McAvoy]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Isaiah Mustafa]], [[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]], [[James Ransone]], [[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]], and [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]], who returns as [[It (character)|Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]. ''It Chapter Two'' premiered at the [[Fox Theater, Westwood Village|Regency Village Theater]] in [[Los Angeles]] on August 26, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on September 6, 2019. The film received praise for its acting (particularly Hader and Skarsg\u00e5rd) and themes, though criticism was aimed at its runtime and weaker scares compared to its predecessor. Its faithfulness to the novel also drew a polarized response.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-chapter-two-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1236289|title='It: Chapter Two': What the Critics Are Saying|author=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 3, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Supercut===\nIn September 2019, Muschietti expressed interest in releasing a \"Supercut\" version of both chapters. This version would combine both films into one with scenes that were left in the editing process. Muschietti also mentioned the possibility of adding two or three new scenes that would be shot for this edition. The existing scenes will not be re-edited. Instead, it will play out as extended versions of both films, with an intermission included to separate the two. The future of this version has not yet been announced, as of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VS4x9uVWOBU&t=405s|title=Director Andy Muschietti tells us why he wants to shoot new scenes for IT |date=September 10, 2019|language=en-US|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Future ===\nIn September 2019, Skarsg\u00e5rd spoke of the possibility of a third installment, saying, \"It would have to be the right type of approach to it. The book ends where the second movie ends, so that is the final chapter of this story. There is this interesting aspect of going back in time before all this happened. There might be a story there that might be worth exploring. Obviously that would be a story that's not in the book, it would be a freestanding story, but obviously within the same universe. So, there might be something interesting out of it. I think it would be fun.\"<ref>https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/08/it-chapter-two-pennywise-bill-skarsgard/</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Dauberman discussed in an interview of the possibility of a third film, saying, \"I do think it's possible. Anything in the Stephen King Universe interests me but there's only so much of the story we could tell in the two movies. There are definitely elements of the novel you could expand on and make its own movie. It's just a question of whether or not people want to see it but I do think It was on this planet for a very, very, very long time and that's a lot of bloodshed and a lot of stories to tell and I think you could do that for sure.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/it-chapter-3-1839759979/amp|title=It Chapter 3: Screenwriter Gary Dauberman Says 'It's Possible'|website=io9.gizmodo.com|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nThe project was in ongoing development since 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|title=It's coming, as Hollywood plans Stephen King adaptation|last=Opie|first=David|date=March 13, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019031106/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/mar/13/stephen-king-it-film-adaptation|archivedate=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|title=The Complete Guide to the 'It' Remake: Stephen King's Pennywise Is Back|last=Dionne|first=Zach|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018085202/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/stephen-king-it-movie-complete-guide-pennywise|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|title=Warner Bros Remaking Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018213742/http://www.slashfilm.com/warner-bros-remaking-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The proposed film adaptations had gone through two major phases of planning: initially with [[Cary Joji Fukunaga|Cary Fukunaga]] from 2009 to 2015, with the early contributions of screenwriter [[David Kajganich]], and with [[Andy Muschietti]], with Fukunaga remaining in some capacity due to prior screenplay contributions.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|title=Stephen King's It \u2013 everything you need to know|last=Williams|first=Owen|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=August 11, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925053809/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/stephen-king-everything-need-know/|archivedate=September 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|title=Updates on the 'Pet Sematary' and 'It' Remakes|last=Schrader|first=Chris|date=July 1, 2010|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018215511/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-pet-sematary-it-remakes-schrad-66877/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Getting Two-Film Adaptation by 'Jane Eyre' Director|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=June 8, 2012|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316153624/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-cary-fukunaga-sandy-178091/|archivedate=March 16, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|title=Cary Fukunaga Explains the Demise of His Unconventional 'IT' Adaptation|last=Fischer|first=Russ|date=September 5, 2015|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214854/http://www.slashfilm.com/cary-fukunaga-it/#more-312794|archivedate=October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== David Kajganich (2009\u20132010) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The thing about Stephen King's writing is that he draws his characters so well, it's hard not to imagine they're real people. So it honestly didn't occur to me to try to think of actors in those roles. Pennywise is a bit of a different story, though. His manner is so crucial to what's frightening about him, and it's too much fun to imagine all of the nuances different actors could give him. I think there are a hundred actors who could each pull off a fascinating, horrifying Pennywise, and I tried not to get too attached to any one actor in my head. I think the Pennywise in this adaptation is a less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality than was [[Tim Curry]]'s Pennywise. I think it will be harder to laugh at his antics since, under the permissiveness of an R rating, I was able to give him back a lot of his more upsetting moments from the novel, ones that could never be aired on network television.\"\n| source = David Kajganich, on the construction of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 INTERVIEW|last=Lilja's Library Editors|first=|work=Lilja's Library|date=June 29, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n}}On March 12, 2009, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] would be bringing [[Stephen King]]'s novel to the big screen, with David Kajganich to adapt King's novel, while Dan Lin, [[Roy Lee]] and Doug Davison would be producing the piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|title=Warner Bros. taps Kajganich for 'It'|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 12, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719080933/http://variety.com/2009/film/features/warner-bros-taps-kajganich-for-it-1118001188/|archivedate=July 19, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> When Kajganich learned of Warner Bros.' plans to adapt King's novel, he went after the job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|title=David Kajganich \u2013 Interview|last=Lilja's Library Editor|first=|date=June 29, 2010|work=Lilja's Library|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808234208/http://liljas-library.com/showinterview.php?id=73|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Knowing that Warner Bros. was committed to adapting ''It'' as a single feature film, Kajganich began to attempt to try to find a structure that would accommodate such a large number of characters in two different time periods, around 120 pages, which was one of Warner Bros.' stipulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Screenwriter Gives Update on Big Screen Adaptation of Stephen King's It|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524144215/http://www.slashfilm.com/screenwriter-gives-update-on-big-screen-adaptation-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich worked with Lin, Lee, and Davison on ''[[The Invasion (film)|The Invasion]]'' (2007), and he knew they would champion good storytelling, and allow him the time to work out a solid first draft of the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|title=Stephen King's \"It\" Bound For Big Screen|last=Castina|first=|date=July 6, 2010|work=PopCrunch|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815153332/http://www.popcrunch.com/it-movie/|archivedate=August 15, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kajganich spoke of the remake being set in the, \"mid-1980s and in the present mirroring the twenty-odd-year gap King uses in the book and with a great deal of care and attention paid to the backstories of all the characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|title=Exclusive: More on the IT Remake! Rated R?|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804120207/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/10860/exclusive-more-on-the-it-remake-rated-r/|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKajganich also mentioned that Warner Bros. wished for the adaptation to be rated R which he furthered by saying, \"we can really honor the book and engage with the traumas that these characters endure.\", while Kajganich spoke of Warner Bros. wanting the adaptation as a single film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|title=Remake of Stephen King's It will be Rated-R and Set in the Mid-1980s|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|date=April 5, 2009|work=[[/Film]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829002848/http://www.slashfilm.com/remake-of-stephen-kings-it-will-be-rated-r-and-set-in-the-mid-1980s/|archivedate=August 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 29, 2010, the screenplay was being re-written by Kajganich.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|title=Early Details on the IT Remake|last=Serafini|first=Matt|date=June 30, 2010|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808233147/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/18143/early-details-on-the-it-remake/|archivedate=August 8, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said that his dream choice for Pennywise would be [[Buster Keaton]] if he were still alive, and the Pennywise that Kajganich scripted being \"less self-conscious of his own irony and surreality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|title=SCREENWRITER DAVID KAJGANICH GIVES AN UPDATE ON STEPHEN KING'S IT|last=Stephens|first=Niki|date=July 1, 2010|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804190540/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/screenwriter-david-kajganich-gives-an-update-on-stephen-kings-it|archivedate=August 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Cary Fukunaga (2012\u20132015) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"I am in the midst of rewriting the first script now.  We're not working on the second part yet. The first script is just about the kids. It's more like ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) meets a horror film. We're definitely honoring the spirit of Stephen King, but the horror has to be modernized to make it relevant. That's my job, right now, on this pass. I'm working on making the horror more about suspense than visualization of any creatures. I just don't think that's scary. What could be there, and the sounds and how it interacts with things, is scarier than actual monsters.\"\n| source = \u2013 Cary Fukunaga, on the development of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|title=Director Cary Fukunaga Talks TRUE DETECTIVE, Making an 8-Hour Film, Future Seasons, BEASTS OF NO NATION, Modernizing Horror with IT, and More|last=Radish|first=Christina|work=[[Collider.com]]|date=January 11, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807054534/http://collider.com/cary-fukunaga-true-detective-interview/|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On June 7, 2012, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''  had revealed that Cary Fukunaga was boarding the project as director and will co-write the script with Chase Palmer, while Roy Lee and Dan Lin are producing, as with [[Seth Grahame-Smith]] and David Katzenberg of KatzSmith Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Be Adapted by Cary Fukunaga into Two Films (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=June 7, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706192550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-be-adapted-by-334899|archivedate=July 6, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, Warner Bros. was announced to have moved the film to its [[New Line Cinema]] division, with overseer duties conducting by New Line's Walter Hamada and Dave Neustadter, along with Vice President of Production at Warner Bros., Niija Kuykendall.<ref name=New>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|title=Stephen King's 'It' Moves From Warner Bros. to New Line (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730140142/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-moves-warner-bros-706062|archivedate=July 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On December 5, 2014, in an interview with ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'', Dan Lin announced that the first film will be a [[coming-of-age]] story about the children tormented by [[It (character)|It]] and the second will skip ahead in time as those same characters band together to continue the fight as adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|title=Stephen King's IT Will Shoot Next Summer|last=Evry|first=Max|date=December 5, 2014|work=Coming Soon|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172056/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/389569-stephen-kings-it-will-shoot-next-summer|archivedate=March 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin also stated that Fukunaga was only committed to directing the first film, though was currently closing a deal to co-write the second. Lin concluded by mentioning King, to which he remarked, \"The most important thing is that [King] gave us his blessing. We didn't want to make this unless he felt it was the right way to go, and when we sent him the script, the response that Cary got back was, 'Go with God, please! This is the version the studio should make.' So that was really gratifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/12/fukunaga-to-shoot-stephen-kings-it-next-summer.html?mid=twitter_vulture#|title=Cary Fukunaga Will Shoot Stephen King's It Next Summer|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|date=December 5, 2014|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> Lin confirmed that Fukunaga would begin [[principal photography]] in Summer 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|title=Stephen King's It remake put on indefinite hold as director Cary Fukunaga walks out|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007150949/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/stephen-kings-it-remake-put-on-indefinite-hold-as-director-cary-fukunaga-walks-out-10275542.html|archivedate=October 7, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2015, Fukunaga was interviewed by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' wherein he spoke about ''It'', while mentioning he has someone in mind for the role of Pennywise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|title=Cary Fukunaga on Adapting It, His Musical With Owen Pallett, and #TrueDetectiveSeason2|last=Wickman|first=Forrest|date=February 3, 2015|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628135946/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/03/cary_fukunaga_on_true_detective_season_2_his_adaption_of_stephen_king_s.html|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 3, 2015, Fukunaga spoke of the film, particularly noting his goal to find the \"perfect guy to play Pennywise\". Fukunaga also revealed that he, Kajganich and Palmer had changed the names and dates in the script, adding, the spirit is similar to what he'd like to see in cinemas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|title='It' Director Seeks \"Perfect Pennywise\" Clown|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=March 3, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624183418/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3334554/director-seeks-perfect-pennywise-clown/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 4, 2015, it was officially announced that [[Will Poulter]] had been cast to play Pennywise, after Fukunaga was \"blown away\" by his audition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|title=Will Poulter cast as Pennywise in Cary Fukunaga's It|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618220510/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/will-poulter-it-pennywise|archivedate=June 18, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WillP\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|title=Will Poulter to Play the Evil Clown in 'It' Remake (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 4, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629051959/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-poutler-pennywise-the-clown-in-new-lines-it-remake-1201446495/|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ty Simpkins]] was considered to play one of The Losers' Club members.<ref name=\"Ty\">{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|title=Jurassic World Interview with Ty Simpkins|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=February 27, 2016|work=[[MovieWeb]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025114439/http://movieweb.com/jurassic-world-interview-ty-simpkins/|archivedate=October 25, 2016|accessdate=October 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2015, it was reported that Fukunaga had dropped out as the director of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|title='It' Loses Director Cary Fukunaga|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709011956/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/it-cary-fukunaga-director-exits-1201504672/|archivedate=July 9, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to [[TheWrap]], Fukunaga clashed with the studio and didn't want to compromise his artistic vision in the wake of budget cuts by New Line, which greenlit the first film at $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|title=Cary Fukunaga Out as Director of Stephen King's 'It' at New Line (Exclusive)|last=Geier|first=Thom|date=May 25, 2015|work=[[The Wrap]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628034157/https://www.thewrap.com/cary-fukunaga-out-as-director-of-stephen-kings-it-at-new-line-exclusive/|archivedate=June 28, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Fukunaga maintained that wasn't the case, with him stating he had bigger disagreements with New Line over the direction of the story: \"I was trying to make an unconventional horror film. It didn't fit into the algorithm of what they knew they could spend and make money back on based on not offending their standard genre audience.\"<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|title=Cary Fukunaga Offers New Details on Why 'It' Remake Fell Apart|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|date=September 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704095044/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/cary-fukunaga-it-exit-1201584416/|archivedate=July 4, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He made mention that the budget was perfectly fine, as well as his desire to make Pennywise more than just the clown.<ref name=\"Cary\" /> Fukunaga concluded by stating, \"We invested years and so much anecdotal storytelling in it. Chase and I both put our childhood in that story. So our biggest fear was they were going to take our script and bastardize it So I'm actually thankful that they are going to rewrite the script. I wouldn't want them to stealing our childhood memories and using that I was honoring King's spirit of it, but I needed to update it. King saw an earlier draft and liked it.\"<ref name=\"Cary\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|title=Cary Fukunaga opens up about IT departure \u2013 Exclusive|last=P. Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=August 17, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108110348/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/17/cary-fukunaga-it-movie?hootPostID=b5145d9e2c7e687d8867d1c08604632f|archivedate=November 8, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On Fukunaga's departure, King wrote, \"The remake of ''IT'' may be dead or undead but we'll always have [[Tim Curry]]. He's still floating down in the sewers of Derry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/602931191281496064|title=The remake of IT may be dead|last=King|first=Stephen|date=May 25, 2015|work=Twitter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322192030/https://twitter.com/StephenKing/status/602931191281496064|archivedate=March 22, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|title=It Remake 'Dead' As Director Walks Away|last=Sky News Editors|first=Justin|date=May 26, 2015|work=[[Sky News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528215629/http://news.sky.com/story/1490944/it-remake-dead-as-director-walks-away|archivedate=May 28, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Andy Muschietti (2015\u20132017) ===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n| quote = \"The way Cary intended to execute the script is something that only he can talk about. I can say my version of ''It'' highly emphasizes Pennywise's most terrifying virtue, which is It's ability to materialise into your worse fear; I want to take people in a journey into Pennywise's world through a disturbing, surrealistic and intoxicating experience that will leave nobody at ease.\"\n| source = \u2013 Andy Muschietti, on his version of ''It''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|title=IT Emphasizes Pennywise's Most Terrifying Virtue|last=Jorissen|first=Matt|work=Lilja's Library|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808225514/http://www.liljas-library.com/article.php?id=4659|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}On July 16, 2015, it was announced that Andy Muschietti was in negotiations to direct ''It'', with New Line beginning a search for a new writer to tailor a script to Muschietti's vision,<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|title=Stephen King's 'It' Finds New Director (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=July 16, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716124053/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-finds-new-director-809080|archivedate=July 16, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|title=Mama's Andr\u00e9s Muschietti in Negotiations To Direct It|last=White|first=James|date=July 17, 2015|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003180808/http://www.empireonline.com/people/andres-muschietti/mama-andres-muschietti-negotiations-direct/|archivedate=October 3, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the announcement also confirming the possible participation of Muschietti's sister, Barbara Muschietti, as a producer, and Richard Brener joining Hamada, Neustadter and Kuykendall to oversee the project.<ref name=\"Andr\u00e9s\" /> On April 22, 2016, it was indicated that Will Poulter, who was originally tapped to portray Pennywise in Fukunaga's version, had dropped out of the film due to a scheduling conflict and that executives were meeting with actors to portray the antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 22, 2016, New Line Cinema set the film for a release of September 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|title=Warner Bros. Sets 'CHiPs', 'It' & Untitled PG-13 Comedy For 2017|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624041157/http://deadline.com/2016/04/chips-it-warner-bros-release-dates-2017-1201742518/|archivedate=June 24, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|title=Warner Bros. Announces Release Date for 'It'|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625020838/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/warner-bros-announces-release-date-for-it-1201759274/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn October 30, 2015, Muschietti was interviewed by ''Variety'' wherein he spoke about his vision of ''It'', while mentioning Poulter was still in the mix for the role of Pennywise: \"[Poulter] would be a great option. For me he is at the top of my list\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|title=Muschiettis to Produce Supernatural Thriller 'Shadows' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Mayorga|first=Emilio|date=October 30, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305002513/http://variety.com/2015/film/global/muschiettis-to-produce-supernatural-thriller-shadows-exclusive-1201630876/|archivedate=March 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He confirmed that next summer is the time for them to start shooting. It was decided to shoot ''It'' during the summer months to give them the time to work with the children who have the main roles in the first part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|title=Filming Starts Next Summer on Remake of Stephen King Classic 'It'|last=Sewell|first=Annie|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[Inquisitr]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519230246/http://www.inquisitr.com/2541256/filming-starts-next-summer-on-remake-of-stephen-kings-it/|archivedate=May 19, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti went on to say that \"King described 50s' terror iconography,\" adding that he feels there is a whole world now to \"rediscover, to update.\" He said there won't be any mummies or werewolves and that the \"terrors are going to be a lot more surprising.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|title=Stephen King's 'It' to Film Next Summer!|last=Disgusting|first=Mr|date=October 31, 2015|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705165415/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3368274/stephen-kings-it-to-film-next-summer/|archivedate=July 5, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 19, 2016, at the [[D.I.C.E. Summit|D.I.C.E. Summit 2016]] producer Roy Lee confirmed that Fukunaga and Chase Palmer's original script had been rewritten, with Lee remarking, \"It will hopefully be shooting later this year. We just got the California tax credit Dauberman wrote the most recent draft working with [Muscetti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|title=Stephen King's It May Start Filming in 2016; Two Movies Still Planned|last=Jones|first=Mike|date=February 19, 2016|work=Screen Rant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625070804/http://screenrant.com/stephen-king-it-movies-filming-2016/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, in an interview with [[Collider.com]], David Kajganich expressed uncertainty as to whether drafts of his original screenplay would be used by Dauberman and Muschietti,<ref name=\"Kajganich\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|title='A Bigger Splash' Writer David Kajganich on His Unique Approach to the Remake and 'It'|last=Page|first=Aubrey|date=May 5, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710194841/http://collider.com/david-kajganich-a-bigger-splash-it-movie-interview/|archivedate=July 10, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with the writer stating, \"We know there's a new director, I don't know myself whether he's going back to any of the previous drafts or writing from scratch. I may not know until the film comes out. I don't know how it works! If you find out let me know.\"<ref name=\"Kajganich\" />\n\nOn June 2, 2016, [[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]] was confirmed to be portraying lead protagonist, Bill Denbrough.<ref name=\"William\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|title='It' Remake to Star 'Midnight Special's\u2019 Jaeden Lieberher|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204208/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/it-remake-jaeden-lieberher-1201787877/|archivedate=July 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] was in final negotiations to star as Pennywise, whose cast will also include [[Finn Wolfhard]], [[Jack Dylan Grazer]], [[Wyatt Oleff]], [[Chosen Jacobs]] and [[Jeremy Ray Taylor]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 2, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622160247/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993|archivedate=June 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 2, 2016, there was a call for 100 background performers, with the background actor call going from 3 p.m. to 7 p.m. and by 4 p.m. more than 300 people had gone through; the casting call also asked for a marching band and period cars between 1970 and 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope//|title=Hundreds turn up for Stephen King's 'It' background actor cast call in Port Hope|last=Northumberland News Editor|first=|date=June 2, 2016|work=Northumberland News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707232022/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/community-story/6704271-hundreds-turn-up-for-stephen-king-s-it-background-actor-cast-call-in-port-hope/|archivedate=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that Owen Teague was set to portray Patrick Hocksetter.<ref name=Hockstetter>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|title='Bloodline' Actor Joins Adaptation of Stephen King's 'It' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619100458/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodline-actor-joins-adaptation-stephen-900672|archivedate=June 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, it was officially announced that [[Nicholas Hamilton]] had been cast to play Henry Bowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|title=Nicholas Hamilton in Stephen King's 'It'; Monterey Media Acquires 'The Last Film Festival'|last=Busch|first=Anita|date=June 21, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626085111/http://deadline.com/2016/06/nicholas-hamilton-joins-stephen-kings-it-the-last-film-festival-gets-theatrical-release-dennis-hopper-1201776453/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 21, 2016, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Javier Botet]] was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Horror Wizard Javier Botet to Haunt 'The Mummy' and Stephen King's 'It'|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=June 21, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030644/http://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3395895/horror-wizard-javier-botet-to-haunt-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|title=Creature Performer Javier Botet Joins The Mummy and Stephen King's It|last=Squires|first=John|date=June 22, 2016|work=[[Dread Central]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623161735/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/172993/creature-performer-javier-botet-joins-mummy-stephen-kings/|archivedate=June 23, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 22, 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Muschietti had chosen actress [[Sophia Lillis]] to portray Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Beverly\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|title=Sophia Lillis Joins New Line's 'It' Remake; Aunjanue Ellis Sign on To Christine Crokos' \u2018Pimp'|last=A. Lincoln|first=Ross|date=June 22, 2015|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627162517/http://deadline.com/2016/06/it-new-line-sophia-lillis-stephen-king-aunjanue-ellis-pimp-1201777627/|archivedate=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On June 24, 2016, [[Moviepilot]] reported that Stephen Bogaert was added to the cast shortly before filming commenced, with Bogaert portraying Al Marsh, the abusive father of Beverly Marsh.<ref name=\"Bogaert\">{{cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|title=Here's The Full Cast List for the New 'IT' Movie|last=Richardson|first=Jancy|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Moviepilot]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629070642/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3978236|archivedate=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2016, Barbara Muschietti was interviewed by ''Northumberland News''{{'}} Karen Longwell, wherein she spoke about the filming locations on ''It'', while mentioning the beauty of Port Hope being one of the reasons as to why it was chosen, while Muschietti added, \"We were looking for an idyllic town, one that would be a strong contrast to the story. Port Hope is the kind of place we all wish we had grown up in: long summers riding bicycles, walks by the lake, a lovely main street, charming homes with green lawns, warm people.\"<ref name=Criss>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p|title=Barbara Muschietti, producer of film based on Stephen King's novel 'It', talks about experience in Port Hope|last=Longwell|first=Karen|work=Northumberland News|date=July 22, 2016|accessdate=July 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725134239/http://www.northumberlandnews.com/news-story/6779167-barbara-muschiette-producer-of-film-based-on-stephen-king-s-novel-it-talks-about-experience-in-p/|archivedate=July 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti also mentioned that 360 extras from the area, from adults to tiny kids, had been involved.<ref name=\"Criss\" />\n\nOn August 11, 2016, at [[The CW]] [[TCA Awards|TCA]] presentation for the upcoming series ''[[Frequency (TV series)|Frequency]]'', producer Dan Lin spoke of the piece's comparison to [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things (TV series)|Stranger Things]]'', with Lee describing ''It'' being a \"homage to 80s movies\", while remarking: \"I think a great analogy is actually Stranger Things, and we're seeing it on Netflix right now. It's very much an homage to '80s movies, whether it's classic Stephen King or even [[Steven Spielberg|Spielberg]]. Think about ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'' (1986) as far as the bonding amongst the kids. But there is a really scary element in Pennywise.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|title='It' Producer Dan Lin Says the Remake Is Like 'Stranger Things'|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=August 11, 2016|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812183907/http://collider.com/it-movie-stranger-things-dan-lin/|archivedate=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lin continued, speaking of how well the young cast has bonded in these first weeks of shooting. Lin stated, \"We clearly had a great dynamic amongst the kids. Really great chemistry is always a challenging thing with a movie like It because you're casting kids who don't have a ton of experience, but it ended up being really natural. Each kid, like a ''[[The Goonies]]'' (1985) or ''Stand by Me'' (1986), has a very specific personality and they're forming the loser's club obviously We've spent a few months getting the kids to bond and now they're going to fight this evil, scary clown.\"<ref name=\"Stranger\" />\n\nOn February 9, 2017, at the press day for ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), Lin confirmed that ''It'' is going to be rated R by the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], to which  he stated to Collider.com{{'}}s Steve Weintraub, \"If you're going to make a \"Rated-R movie\", you have to fully embrace what it is, and you have to embrace the source material. It is a scary clown that's trying to kill kids. They do have a scary clown that's taken over the town of Derry, so it's going to be rated R.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|title=Producer Dan Lin Confirms \u2018It\u2019 Rating and Sequel Plans|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=February 9, 2017|work=[[Collider.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313125903/http://collider.com/it-remake-rated-r-sequel-adults/#pennywise|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On March 11, 2017, Muschietti, at the [[SXSW]] festival, spoke of an element of the [[pre-production]] phase in his attempt to keep Skarsg\u00e5rd separated from the film's child actors, wherein the actor wasn't introduced to the young cast until Pennywise's first encounter with the children:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|title=SXSW 2017: Impressions of First Footage from IT & New Footage from ANNABELLE 2|last=Wixson|first=Heather|date=March 12, 2017|work=Daily Dead|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313131627/http://dailydead.com/sxsw-2017-impressions-first-footage-new-footage-annabelle-2/|archivedate=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"It was something that we agreed on, and that's how it happened The day that he showed up on the stage, they fucking freaked out. Bill is like, seven-foot high, and I can't describe how scary he looks in person. He's a wiry man, crouching, making sounds, snotting, drooling, speaking in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] sometimes. Terrifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|title=The new Pennywise terrified the young cast of Stephen King\u2019s IT reboot|last=Farokhmanesh|first=Megan|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312200748/http://www.theverge.com/2017/3/12/14897214/it-reboot-pennywise-preview-sxsw-2017|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti stated that the story had been moved forward, with the scenes with the young Losers Club shifting from the 1950s to the 1980s, while also describing their plot as \"getting much wider,\" with new material not in the novel or the [[It (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]].<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|title=SXSW Panel: Face Your Fears|last=Whittaker|first=Richard|date=March 12, 2017|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312102610/http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/sxsw/2017-03-12/sxsw-panel-face-your-fears/|archivedate=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, Muschietti said he hoped it would still strike the same emotional resonance that the book did for him when he first read it: \"It's all about trying to hit the core and the heart.\"<ref name=\"SXSW\" />\n\nOn July 12, 2017, Muschietti, in an interview with French magazine ''Mad Movies'', spoke of when developing the R rated film, in which allowed him to go into very adult themes, which was championed from the people at New Line Cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mad-movies.com/fr/module/99999735/4495/ca-d-andy-muschietti|title=\u00c7A BY ANDY MUSCHIETTI|last=Mad Movies Editors|first=|date=July 12, 2017|work=Mad Movies|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|title=New Pennywise Image Found On French Magazine Cover|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 3, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704024519/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3444929/new-pennywise-image-found-french-magazine-cover/|archivedate=July 4, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also stated that, \"if you aimed for a PG-13 movie, you had nothing at the end. So we were very lucky that the producers didn't try to stop us. In fact it's more our own moral compass that sometimes showed us that some things lead us in places where we didn't want to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|title=Andy Muschietti Talks Holding Nothing Back for \"R\"-rated \u2018IT\u2019|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716093735/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446886/andy-muschietti-talks-holding-nothing-back-r-rated/|archivedate=July 16, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/07/it-director-andy-muschietti-on-the-films-r-rating/|title=It director Andy Muschietti on the film\u2019s R rating|last=Collinson|first=Gary|date=July 16, 2017|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In the same interview, on July 12, 2017, producer Barbara Muschietti added that there was only one scene that was deemed to be too horrific to feature in the new adaptation, in which she stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unilad.co.uk/film/new-it-film-will-contain-scenes-too-intense-for-the-original/|title=New IT Film Will Contain Scenes \u2018Too Intense\u2019 For The Original|last=Murray|first=Emily|date=July 16, 2017|work=[[UniLad]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> \"you won't find the scene where a kid has his back broken and is thrown in the toilets. We thought that the visual translation of that scene had something that was really too much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|title=The New 'IT' Movie Will Be \"R\" Rated With \"Very Adult Themes\"|last=Naylor|first=Daisy|date=July 16, 2017|work=thehooknew|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808035223/http://thehookmag.com/2017/07/new-movie-will-r-rated-adult-themes-143903/|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/director-muschetti-talks-advantages-r-rating/|title=IT Director Talks the Advantages of an R Rating|last=Carptenter|first=Michael|date=July 16, 2017|work=iHorror|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti concluded by emphasizing that nothing was removed from the original vision, nor was the violence of any event watered down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|title=IT Director: R Rating Allows Film to Explore \u2018Very Adult Themes\u2019|last=Kennedy|first=Michael|date=July 14, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717232034/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-rating-adult-story/|archivedate=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2017, in an interview with ''Variety''{{'}}s Brent Lang, director Muschietti commented of the monstrous forms that It shall be taking, as well as noting the fact that they'll be very different from the incarnations present in King's story, in which he stated,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|title=Various Monsters in \u2018IT\u2019 Will Be Very Different from the Book|last=Squires|first=John|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720010749/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3448025/various-monsters-will-different-book/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"The story is the same, but there are changes in the things the kids are scared of. In the book they're children in the 50s, so the incarnations of the monsters are mainly from movies, so it's [[Larry Talbot|Wolf Man]], [[Imhotep (The Mummy)|the Mummy]], [[Frankenstein's monster|Frankenstein]], and [[Count Dracula|Dracula]]. I had a different approach. I wanted to bring out deeper fears, based not only on movie monsters but on childhood traumas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/director-says-stephen-king-s-it-will-not-feature-the-classic-movie-monsters-641|title=ANDY MUSCHIETTI TALKS IT PART 2 & CLASSIC MOVIE MONSTERS|last=Sprague|first=Mike|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|title=There's new terrifying details about the IT film|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Joe (website)|Joe]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720120650/https://www.joe.co.uk/entertainment/theres-new-terrifying-details-about-the-it-film-134555|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> While on the topic of what being the key to a successful horror film, Muschietti concluded by remarking that \"Stay true to what scares you. If you don't respect that, you can't scare anyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|title=\u2018It\u2019 Director on Tackling the Two R-Rated Movies and Why He Picked Bill Skarsgard for Pennywise|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719214312/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-director-andres-muschietti-two-movies-bill-skarsgard-1202499038/amp/|archivedate=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Muschietti explained how Skarsg\u00e5rd caught his attention to embody Pennywise, while pointing out that he didn't want the young cast to spend too much time with the actor when not shooting, and encouraged the cast to \"maintain distance\" between them, wherein Muschietti detailed:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/movies/movie-news/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-sequel-1075855.html|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=Female First Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=Female First|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|title=Andres Muschietti confirms prep date for IT sequel|last=MSN Editors|first=|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[MSN]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808033345/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/andres-muschietti-confirms-prep-date-for-it-sequel/ar-AAoulDR|archive-date=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> We wanted to carry the impact of the encounters to when the cameras were rolling. The first scene where Bill interacted with the children, it was fun to see how the plan worked. The kids were really, really creeped out by Bill. He's pretty intimidating because he's six-four and has all this makeup.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/movies/2017/07/19/stephen-kings-it-remake-pennywise-bill-skarasgard/|title=Stephen King's 'It' Director Explains How Bill Skarsgard Won Coveted Pennywise Role|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=July 19, 2017|work=Pop Culture|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2016, producer [[Roy Lee]], in an interview with Collider, mentioned a second ''It'' film, remarking, \"[Dauberman] wrote the most recent draft working with [Muschietti], so it's being envisioned as two movies.\"<ref name=\"Muschietti\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|title=Exclusive: 'It' Movie Hopefully Shooting This Year; Will Be Rated-R|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=February 19, 2016|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626211828/http://collider.com/it-movie-news-rating/|archivedate=June 26, 2016|accessdate=June 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, Muschietti revealed that production was set to begin in the spring of 2018, adding,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti Says He's Coming Back for a Sequel|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720053246/http://collider.com/it-part-2-director-andy-muschietti/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|title=Second IT Movie Adaptation Aims to Start Filming Next Year|last=Zinski|first=Dan|date=July 19, 2017|work=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721010304/http://screenrant.com/it-movie-sequel-filming-2018-start/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"We'll probably have a script for the second part in January [2018]. Ideally, we would start prep in March. Part one is only about the kids. Part two is about these characters 27 years later as adults, with flashbacks to 1989 when they were kids.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|title=STEPHEN KING'S IT ALREADY HAS A SEQUEL PLANNED|last=Wax|first=Alyse|date=July 20, 2017|work=[[Syfy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720065345/http://www.syfy.com/syfywire/it-already-has-a-sequel-planned|archivedate=July 20, 2017|accessdate=July 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 21, 2017, Muschietti spoke of looking forward to having a dialogue in the second film that does not exist within the first, stating, \"... it seems like we're going to do it. It's the second half, it's not a sequel. It's the second half and it's very connected to the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-andy-muschietti-interview-sdcc/|title='IT' Director Andy Muschietti on Reinventing Pennywise and Sequel Plans|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 21, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1683730/why-the-it-movie-left-the-adult-storyline-out-of-the-first-film|title=Why The IT Movie Left The Adult Storyline Out Of The First Film|last=O'Connell|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2017|work=CinemaBlend|accessdate=July 23, 2017}}</ref> Muschietti stated that two cut scenes from the first film will possibly be included in the second, one of which being the fire at the Black Spot from the book.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/it-movie-cut-scenes|title=The 'IT' Movie Had to Cut Two Crazy Scenes to Stay On-Budget|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=July 27, 2017|work=Collider.com|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that the sequel would be released on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-movie-sequel-release-date-1202570309/|title='It' Sequel Sets September 2019 Release Date|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Variety.com]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> with [[Gary Dauberman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/it-sequel-plans-moving-forward-at-new-line-1035456|title='It' Movie Sequel Plans Move Forward at New Line|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=September 7, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref> and Jeffrey Jurgensen (who later went uncredited)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/are-you-afraid-of-the-dark-movie-release-1202632308/|title=''Are You Afraid Of The Dark?'' Movie Gets October 2019 Release|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=Variety|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref> writing the script. Andy Muschietti returned to direct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/it-sequel-official-writer-gary-dauberman-1202550077/|title='It' Sequel Moves Ahead With Screenwriter Gary Dauberman|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|date=September 7, 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=September 26, 2017}}</ref> Dauberman would later leave the project to write and direct ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]'', while [[Jason Fuchs]] was brought in as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |url=https://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|title=''It 2'' Filmmakers on How Jason Fuchs Helped Bring the Sequel Script to the Finish Line |date=July 22, 2019 |work=Collider |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916055021/http://collider.com/it-2-script-gary-dauberman-jason-fuchs/|archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Recurring cast and characters ==\n{{Cast indicator|A|C|O|V|Y}}\n<!--Only put characters that have a roles within both films.-->{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Characters\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center:\" |Films\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2017\n! scope=\"col\" |2019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[It (character)|It / Pennywise the Dancing Clown]]\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Bill Denbrough]]\n|[[Jaeden Martell|Jaeden Lieberher]]\n|[[James McAvoy]]<hr>Jaeden Lieberher{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Beverly Marsh]]\n|[[Sophia Lillis]]\n|[[Jessica Chastain]]<hr>Sophia Lillis{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Hanscom\n|[[Jeremy Ray Taylor]]\n|[[Jay Ryan (actor)|Jay Ryan]]<hr>Jeremy Ray Taylor{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Richie Tozier]]\n|[[Finn Wolfhard]]\n|[[Bill Hader]]<hr>Finn Wolfhard{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eddie Kaspbrak]]\n|[[Jack Dylan Grazer]]\n|[[James Ransone]]<hr>Jack Dylan Grazer{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Stanley Uris\n|[[Wyatt Oleff]]\n|[[Andy Bean (actor)|Andy Bean]]<hr>Wyatt Oleff{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mike Hanlon\n|[[Chosen Jacobs]]\n|[[Isaiah Mustafa]]<hr>Chosen Jacobs{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Tristian Levi Cox{{ref|young|Y}}<hr>Torian Matthew{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Henry Bowers\n|[[Nicholas Hamilton]]\n|Teach Grant<hr>Nicholas Hamilton{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Georgie Denbrough]]\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jackson Robert Scott]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patrick Hockstetter\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Owen Teague]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alvin Marsh \n|colspan=\"2\"| Stephen Bogaert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sonia Kaspbrak / Myra\n|colspan=\"2\"| Molly Atkinson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mr. Keene\n|colspan=\"2\"| Joe Bostick\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Gretta Keene\n|[[Megan Charpentier]]\n|Juno Rinaldi<hr>Megan Charpentier{{ref|young|Y}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |The Hobo / The Leper /<br>The Witch\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Javier Botet]]\n|}\n\n== Additional crew and production details ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;width:40%;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Role\n! colspan=\"2\" |Films\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It (2017 film)|It]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:12%;\" |''[[It Chapter Two]]''\n|-\n!2017\n!2019\n|-\n!Composer(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n|-\n!Cinematography\n|[[Chung Chung-hoon|Chung-hoon Chung]]\n|Checco Varese\n|-\n!Editor(s)\n|colspan=\"2\"| [[Jason Ballantine]]\n|-\n!Production company\n|[[New Line Cinema]]<hr>[[RatPac-Dune Entertainment]]<hr>[[Vertigo Entertainment]]<hr>Lin Pictures<hr>[[KatzSmith Productions]]\n|New Line Cinema<hr>Double Dream<hr>Vertigo Entertainment<hr>Rideback\n|-\n!Distributor\n| co